{"title_page": "Market Harborough railway station", "text_new": "{{short description|Railway station in Leicestershire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK station\n| symbol       = rail\n| name         = Market Harborough\n| image_name   = MarketHarboroughTown-10.jpg\n| caption      = The [[Grade II listed]] station building from 1884 by [[John Livock]]\n| manager      = [[East Midlands Railway]]\n| locale       = [[Market Harborough]]\n| borough      = [[Harborough District|Harborough]]\n| code         = MHR\n| dft_category = C2\n| start        = 1 May 1850\n| platforms    = 2\n<!-- | usage0203    =\n| usage0304    =\n| usage0405    = {{pad}}0.575\n| usage0506    = {{increase}} 0.594\n| usage0607    = {{increase}} 0.660\n| usage0708    = {{increase}} 0.701\n| usage0809 = {{increase}} 0.718\n| usage0910 = {{decrease}} 0.675\n| usage1011 = {{increase}} 0.720 \n| usage1112 = {{increase}} 0.746 \n| usage1213 = {{increase}} 0.765\n| usage1314 = {{increase}} 0.798 -->\n| usage1415 = {{increase}} 0.832\n| usage1516 = {{increase}} 0.870\n| usage1617 = {{increase}} 0.888\n| usage1718 = {{increase}} 0.894\n| usage1819 = {{increase}} 0.908\n| coordinates  = {{coord|52.48|-0.9094|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| gridref      = SP741874\n| listing_grade    = [[Grade II listed]]\n| listing_detail   = Market Harborough Railway Station\n| listing_start    = 25 March 1975\n| listing_amended  = \n| listing_entry    = 1074404\n| listing_reference= <ref name=\"Listing\"/>\n}}\n[[File:Market Harborough railway station 2174946 4fb3f674.jpg|thumb|right|275px|Market Harborough Station in 1957]]\n'''Market Harborough railway station''' is a [[Grade II listed]]<ref name=\"Listing\">{{National Heritage List for England|num= 1074404|desc=Market Harborough Railway Station |access-date=4 January 2017 |mode=cs2}}</ref> station which serves the town of [[Market Harborough]] in [[Leicestershire]], [[England]]. It is situated to the east of the town centre and lies on the [[Midland Main Line]], 16 miles (26&nbsp;km) south-east of [[Leicester railway station|Leicester]].\n\n==History==\nThe original station was opened on 1 May 1850<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Market Harborough. The Rugby and Stamford Railway|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000317/18500504/013/0003 |newspaper=Northampton Mercury |location=British Newspaper Archive |date=4 May 1850 |access-date=6 July 2016 }}</ref> by the [[London and North Western Railway|London and North Western Railway (LNWR)]] on the [[Rugby railway station|Rugby]] to [[Stamford railway station|Stamford]] branch of its main line from [[Euston railway station|London Euston]] to Birmingham and the north-west. The [[Midland Railway]] shared this station from 1857 when it built its extension from [[Leicester railway station|Leicester]] to [[Bedford railway station|Bedford]] and [[Hitchin railway station|Hitchin]]. On 16 February 1859 the LNWR opened a further branch line, from [[Northampton railway station|Northampton]] to Market Harborough, which also used the same station.<ref name=\"Leleux\"/>\n\nThe station was the scene of a serious accident on 28 August 1862.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Dreadful accident on the Midland Railway at Market Harborough|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000237/18840919/008/0004 |newspaper=Leicestershire Mercury |location=British Newspaper Archive |date=30 August 1862 |access-date=6 July 2016 }}</ref>  An excursion train bound for [[Burton-upon-Trent railway station|Burton-upon-Trent]] stopped to pick up water, and a second train bound for Leicester collided with the rear of it. The accident resulted in the death of one person and seventy were injured.\n\nAs traffic built up, the Midland opened a new line on 26 June 1885 at a higher elevation, crossing the LNWR and then running parallel to a new joint station in the present position.\n\nThe new station building was opened on 14 September 1884.<ref name=\"Leleux\">{{cite book |last= Leleux |first=Robin|date= |title=A Regional History of the Railways of Great Britain. Volume 9 |url= |location= |publisher=David & Charles, Newton Abbot |page=107 |isbn=0715371657}}</ref> It was built by Parnell and Sons of Rugby from designs by [[John Livock]] and Millbank. The engineer was Hirst of Rugby.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Market Harborough. The new railway station |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000237/18840919/008/0004\n |newspaper=Stamford Mercury |location=British Newspaper Archive |date=19 September 1884 |access-date=6 July 2016 }}</ref>\n\nMarket Harborough was the largest station within the county boundary south of Leicester. Such was the volume of traffic, a junction for five different directions at its height, by 1870 plans for an engine shed were released in addition to the already provided loco pit, turntable and water tank. A shed was never built but this did not stop it becoming a sub-shed of Leicester in later years.\n\nThe service on the original LNWR line was drastically reduced in 1960 and it finally closed in June 1966.  Freight traffic on the line to Northampton continued until closure in August 1981, when the station ceased to be a junction. The Midland line continues, with the platform buildings and canopies replaced with modern designs in the sixties. The main building survived, however, and was carefully restored in 1981.\n\n==Services==\n[[File:Emtmap.png|thumb|A Map of East Midlands Railway InterCity services showing the current service pattern each hour]]\n\nMarket Harborough is served by the fast and semi-fast [[East Midlands Railway]] [[British Rail Class 222|Class 222 \"Meridian\"]]/[[British Rail Class 43 (HST)|HST]] services. Trains to London are around every half hour and all off peak trains now start or end at [[Nottingham]]. One of these are fast going non-stop to or from London. While the other is a semi-fast service via {{stnlnk|Kettering}}, {{stnlnk|Wellingborough}}, {{stnlnk|Bedford}} and {{stnlnk|Luton Airport Parkway}}. Services north to Nottingham call at {{stnlnk|Leicester}} and either {{stnlnk|Loughborough}} and {{stnlnk|Beeston}} or {{stnlnk|East Midlands Parkway}}. In the morning and evening some services are extended to [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]] via [[Newark-on-Trent|Newark]].<ref>[http://www.eastmidlandstrains.co.uk/NR/rdonlyres/A563C19B-07D3-42D6-A6CF-5B14526ECB20/0/Route1TimetableDec09.pdf East Midlands Trains: Timetable 13 December 2009 to 22 May 2010] Accessed 13 March 2010</ref>\n\nWith a journey time to London of just over one hour, the frequency of trains to the capital in the morning and evening peak is excellent for [[commuting]], with a train running (occasionally non stop) every twenty minutes with the quickest journeys taking fifty-five minutes.\n\nWeekend services include trains operating to [[York]] and, in the summer, [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]].\n\nBus services depart from outside the station and operate throughout the town and also to both [[Lutterworth]], [[Hinckley]] and Leicester.\n\nThe initial specification for the East Midlands Trains franchise, which started in 2007, would have seen a big reduction in the number of trains calling at Market Harborough.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dft.gov.uk/stellent/groups/dft_railways/documents/page/dft_railways_611833.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 October 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060723042155/http://www.dft.gov.uk/stellent/groups/dft_railways/documents/page/dft_railways_611833.pdf |archivedate=23 July 2006 }}</ref>  These plans were fought against by the Harborough Rail Users' Group, and, as a result, the final specification saw no reduction in services.<ref>[http://www.harboroughtoday.co.uk/ViewArticle2.aspx?SectionID=760&ArticleID=1640774 Passengers fight back over rail cuts - Harborough Today<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n[[Stagecoach Group|Stagecoach]] promised as part of their bid that they would create additional car parking spaces at stations along their route, Market Harborough's new larger car park opened early in 2008.<ref>[http://www.eastmidlandstrains.co.uk/EMTrains/AboutUs/News/_ExtraCarParkSpacesAtMarketHarborough.htm Extra Car Park Spaces at Market Harborough - East Midlands Trains<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nMarket Harborough is a [[Penalty fare]] station, meaning that as there are facilities to buy tickets at the station, a valid ticket or [[Permit to travel]] must be shown when requested, rather than being able to buy tickets on the train.\n\n==Future==\n\n===Market Harborough Line Speed Improvement project===\n\nMarket Harborough station is located on a large curve on the [[Midland Main Line]] and as a result of this line speeds through the station have always been relatively slow, at around {{convert|60|mph|-1|abbr=on}}. The track layout is set to change significantly as [[Network Rail]] engineers set about straightening the line as part of their overall plan to increase line speeds. It is also planned that both platforms will be extended. This work was originally scheduled to be complete by no later than 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkrail.co.uk/documents/6182_Enhancements%20Document%20Dec%202009.pdf |title=Network Rail CP4 Delivery Plan 2009 Enhancements programme: statement of scope, outputs and milestones |accessdate=2010-03-18 |publisher=Network Rail |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607022101/http://www.networkrail.co.uk/documents/6182_Enhancements%20Document%20Dec%202009.pdf |archivedate=7 June 2011 }}</ref> but was completed by the end of 2019.\n\nThe Market Harborough Line Speed Improvement project will deliver:\n\n* A straighter line, enabling a line speed increase through Market Harborough and a reduction in journey time for passengers travelling between London and Sheffield\n* A new 265m platform 1 and extended platform 2 to accommodate longer trains with more seats\n* A new footbridge with lifts\n* A new 300 space car park on the east side of the station (completed in 2018).  Work to increase this in size to 500 spaces started in the summer of 2019 once the new track has been installed and tied in to the existing lines, freeing up the required space.<ref>{{cite web| title=Market Harborough Line Speed Improvement project|url=https://www.networkrail.co.uk/running-the-railway/our-routes/lne-and-em/midland-main-line-improvement-programme/market-harborough-line-speed-improvement-project|publisher = Network Rail|accessdate=19 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Electrification===\n\nSee also [[Midland Main Line#Electrification|''Electrification of the Midland Main Line'']]\n\nThe railway through Leicestershire is not electrified and therefore all services are operated by diesel trains. Plans to electrify this part of the line (as part of the wider [[Electric Spine]] project), announced in 2012<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.gov.uk/government/news/investing-in-rail-investing-in-jobs-and-growth|title= Investing in rail, investing in jobs and growth |date=16 July 2012 |publisher=Department for Transport}}</ref> and later resumed after a pause in 2015,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.gov.uk/government/news/transpennine-and-midland-mainline-electrification-works-to-resume|title= TransPennine and Midland Mainline electrification works to resume |date=30 September 2015 |publisher=Department for Transport}}</ref> were cancelled in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/policy/single-view/view/sheffield-swansea-and-windermere-electrification-cancelled.html|title= Sheffield, Swansea and Windermere electrification cancelled|website=Railway Gazette|date=20 July 2017}}</ref> However, in February 2019 [[Andrew Jones (British politician)|Andrew Jones]], Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Transport, announced that electrification would be extended northwards from Kettering up to Market Harborough, enabling the connection of the railway to a new power supply point at Braybrooke.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/news/uk/single-view/view/electrification-to-reach-market-harborough.html|title=Electrification to reach Market Harborough|website=Railway Gazette|date=5 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.railway-technology.com/news/uk-to-extend-electrification-of-midland-main-line|title=UK to extend electrification of Midland Main Line|website=Railway Technology|date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Service summary==\n{{rail start}}\n{{s-rail-national|previous=Leicester|next=St Pancras International|toc=East Midlands Railway|route=Midland Main Line|rowsmid=2|rows1=2}}\n{{s-rail-national|previous=Leicester|next=Kettering|toc=East Midlands Railway|route=Midland Main Line|hidemid=yes|hide1=yes}}\n{{Historical Rail Insert}}\n{{Rail line|previous=[[East Langton railway station|East Langton]]<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small> |next=[[Desborough railway station|Desborough and Rothwell]]<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small> |route=[[Midland Railway]]<br><small>[[Midland Main Line]]</small>|col={{MR colour}}}}\n{{Disused Rail Insert}}\n{{Rail line|previous=[[Lubenham railway station|Lubenham]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |next=[[Ashley and Weston railway station|Ashley and Weston]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route=[[London and North Western Railway]]<br><small>[[Rugby and Stamford Railway|Rugby to Peterborough East]]</small>|col={{LNWR colour}}}}\n{{Rail line|previous=[[Clipston and Oxendon railway station|Clipston and Oxendon]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |next=[[Hallaton railway station|Hallaton]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route=[[London and North Western Railway]]<br><small>Northampton to Nottingham</small>|col={{LNWR colour}}}}\n{{rail end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Market Harborough railway station}}\n{{stn art lnk|MHR|LE167QE}}\n\n{{Leicestershire and Rutland railway stations}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:Former London and North Western Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Former Midland Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1850]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by East Midlands Railway]]\n[[Category:Market Harborough]]\n[[Category:John William Livock buildings]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed railway stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Railway station in Leicestershire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox UK station\n| symbol       = rail\n| name         = Market Harborough\n| image_name   = MarketHarboroughTown-10.jpg\n| caption      = The [[Grade II listed]] station building from 1884 by [[John Livock]]\n| manager      = [[East Midlands Railway]]\n| locale       = [[Market Harborough]]\n| borough      = [[Harborough District|Harborough]]\n| code         = MHR\n| dft_category = C2\n| start        = 1 May 1850\n| platforms    = 2\n<!-- | usage0203    =\n| usage0304    =\n| usage0405    = {{pad}}0.575\n| usage0506    = {{increase}} 0.594\n| usage0607    = {{increase}} 0.660\n| usage0708    = {{increase}} 0.701\n| usage0809 = {{increase}} 0.718\n| usage0910 = {{decrease}} 0.675\n| usage1011 = {{increase}} 0.720 \n| usage1112 = {{increase}} 0.746 \n| usage1213 = {{increase}} 0.765\n| usage1314 = {{increase}} 0.798 -->\n| usage1415 = {{increase}} 0.832\n| usage1516 = {{increase}} 0.870\n| usage1617 = {{increase}} 0.888\n| usage1718 = {{increase}} 0.894\n| usage1819 = {{increase}} 0.908\n| coordinates  = {{coord|52.48|-0.9094|type:railwaystation_region:GB_scale:10000|display=inline,title}}\n| gridref      = SP741874\n| listing_grade    = [[Grade II listed]]\n| listing_detail   = Market Harborough Railway Station\n| listing_start    = 25 March 1975\n| listing_amended  = \n| listing_entry    = 1074404\n| listing_reference= <ref name=\"Listing\"/>\n}}\n[[File:Market Harborough railway station 2174946 4fb3f674.jpg|thumb|right|275px|Market Harborough Station in 1957]]\n'''Market Harborough railway station''' is a [[Grade II listed]]<ref name=\"Listing\">{{National Heritage List for England|num= 1074404|desc=Market Harborough Railway Station |access-date=4 January 2017 |mode=cs2}}</ref> station which serves the town of [[Market Harborough]] in [[Leicestershire]], [[England]]. It is situated to the east of the town centre and lies on the [[Midland Main Line]], 16 miles (26&nbsp;km) south-east of [[Leicester railway station|Leicester]].\n\n==History==\nThe original station was opened on 1 May 1850<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Market Harborough. The Rugby and Stamford Railway|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000317/18500504/013/0003 |newspaper=Northampton Mercury |location=British Newspaper Archive |date=4 May 1850 |access-date=6 July 2016 }}</ref> by the [[London and North Western Railway|London and North Western Railway (LNWR)]] on the [[Rugby railway station|Rugby]] to [[Stamford railway station|Stamford]] branch of its main line from [[Euston railway station|London Euston]] to Birmingham and the north-west. The [[Midland Railway]] shared this station from 1857 when it built its extension from [[Leicester railway station|Leicester]] to [[Bedford railway station|Bedford]] and [[Hitchin railway station|Hitchin]]. On 16 February 1859 the LNWR opened a further branch line, from [[Northampton railway station|Northampton]] to Market Harborough, which also used the same station.<ref name=\"Leleux\"/>\n\nThe station was the scene of a serious accident on 28 August 1862.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Dreadful accident on the Midland Railway at Market Harborough|url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000237/18840919/008/0004 |newspaper=Leicestershire Mercury |location=British Newspaper Archive |date=30 August 1862 |access-date=6 July 2016 }}</ref>  An excursion train bound for [[Burton-upon-Trent railway station|Burton-upon-Trent]] stopped to pick up water, and a second train bound for Leicester collided with the rear of it. The accident resulted in the death of one person and seventy were injured.\n\nAs traffic built up, the Midland opened a new line on 26 June 1885 at a higher elevation, crossing the LNWR and then running parallel to a new joint station in the present position.\n\nThe new station building was opened on 14 September 1884.<ref name=\"Leleux\">{{cite book |last= Leleux |first=Robin|date= |title=A Regional History of the Railways of Great Britain. Volume 9 |url= |location= |publisher=David & Charles, Newton Abbot |page=107 |isbn=0715371657}}</ref> It was built by Parnell and Sons of Rugby from designs by [[John Livock]] and Millbank. The engineer was Hirst of Rugby.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Market Harborough. The new railway station |url=http://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0000237/18840919/008/0004\n |newspaper=Stamford Mercury |location=British Newspaper Archive |date=19 September 1884 |access-date=6 July 2016 }}</ref>\n\nMarket Harborough was the largest station within the county boundary south of Leicester. Such was the volume of traffic, a junction for five different directions at its height, by 1870 plans for an engine shed were released in addition to the already provided loco pit, turntable and water tank. A shed was never built but this did not stop it becoming a sub-shed of Leicester in later years.\n\nThe service on the original LNWR line was drastically reduced in 1960 and it finally closed in June 1966.  Freight traffic on the line to Northampton continued until closure in August 1981, when the station ceased to be a junction. The Midland line continues, with the platform buildings and canopies replaced with modern designs in the sixties. The main building survived, however, and was carefully restored in 1981.\n\n==Services==\n[[File:Emtmap.png|thumb|A Map of East Midlands Railway InterCity services showing the current service pattern each hour]]\n\nMarket Harborough is served by the fast and semi-fast [[East Midlands Railway]] [[British Rail Class 222|Class 222 \"Meridian\"]]/[[British Rail Class 43 (HST)|HST]] services. Trains to London are around every half hour and all off peak trains now start or end at [[Nottingham]]. One of these are fast going non-stop to or from London. While the other is a semi-fast service via {{stnlnk|Kettering}}, {{stnlnk|Wellingborough}}, {{stnlnk|Bedford}} and {{stnlnk|Luton Airport Parkway}}. Services north to Nottingham call at {{stnlnk|Leicester}} and either {{stnlnk|Loughborough}} and {{stnlnk|Beeston}} or {{stnlnk|East Midlands Parkway}}. In the morning and evening some services are extended to [[Lincoln, Lincolnshire|Lincoln]] via [[Newark-on-Trent|Newark]].<ref>[http://www.eastmidlandstrains.co.uk/NR/rdonlyres/A563C19B-07D3-42D6-A6CF-5B14526ECB20/0/Route1TimetableDec09.pdf East Midlands Trains: Timetable 13 December 2009 to 22 May 2010] Accessed 13 March 2010</ref>\n\nWith a journey time to London of just over one hour, the frequency of trains to the capital in the morning and evening peak is excellent for [[commuting]], with a train running (occasionally non stop) every twenty minutes with the quickest journeys taking fifty-five minutes.\n\nWeekend services include trains operating to [[York]] and, in the summer, [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]].\n\nBus services depart from outside the station and operate throughout the town and also to both [[Lutterworth]], [[Hinckley]] and Leicester.\n\nThe initial specification for the East Midlands Trains franchise, which started in 2007, would have seen a big reduction in the number of trains calling at Market Harborough.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dft.gov.uk/stellent/groups/dft_railways/documents/page/dft_railways_611833.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=15 October 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060723042155/http://www.dft.gov.uk/stellent/groups/dft_railways/documents/page/dft_railways_611833.pdf |archivedate=23 July 2006 }}</ref>  These plans were fought against by the Harborough Rail Users' Group, and, as a result, the final specification saw no reduction in services.<ref>[http://www.harboroughtoday.co.uk/ViewArticle2.aspx?SectionID=760&ArticleID=1640774 Passengers fight back over rail cuts - Harborough Today<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n[[Stagecoach Group|Stagecoach]] promised as part of their bid that they would create additional car parking spaces at stations along their route, Market Harborough's new larger car park opened early in 2008.<ref>[http://www.eastmidlandstrains.co.uk/EMTrains/AboutUs/News/_ExtraCarParkSpacesAtMarketHarborough.htm Extra Car Park Spaces at Market Harborough - East Midlands Trains<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nMarket Harborough is a [[Penalty fare]] station, meaning that as there are facilities to buy tickets at the station, a valid ticket or [[Permit to travel]] must be shown when requested, rather than being able to buy tickets on the train.\n\n==Future==\n\n===Market Harborough Line Speed Improvement project===\n\nMarket Harborough station is located on a large curve on the [[Midland Main Line]] and as a result of this line speeds through the station have always been relatively slow, at around {{convert|60|mph|-1|abbr=on}}. The track layout is set to change significantly as [[Network Rail]] engineers set about straightening the line as part of their overall plan to increase line speeds. It is also planned that both platforms will be extended. This work was originally scheduled to be complete by no later than 2012<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.networkrail.co.uk/documents/6182_Enhancements%20Document%20Dec%202009.pdf |title=Network Rail CP4 Delivery Plan 2009 Enhancements programme: statement of scope, outputs and milestones |accessdate=2010-03-18 |publisher=Network Rail |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607022101/http://www.networkrail.co.uk/documents/6182_Enhancements%20Document%20Dec%202009.pdf |archivedate=7 June 2011 }}</ref> but was completed by the end of 2019.\n\nThe Market Harborough Line Speed Improvement project will deliver:\n\n* A straighter line, enabling a line speed increase through Market Harborough and a reduction in journey time for passengers travelling between London and Sheffield\n* A new 265m platform 1 and extended platform 2 to accommodate longer trains with more seats\n* A new footbridge with lifts\n* A new 300 space car park on the east side of the station (completed in 2018).  Work to increase this in size to 500 spaces will start in the summer of 2019 once the new track has been installed and tied in to the existing lines, freeing up the required space.<ref>{{cite web| title=Market Harborough Line Speed Improvement project|url=https://www.networkrail.co.uk/running-the-railway/our-routes/lne-and-em/midland-main-line-improvement-programme/market-harborough-line-speed-improvement-project|publisher = Network Rail|accessdate=19 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Electrification===\n\nSee also [[Midland Main Line#Electrification|''Electrification of the Midland Main Line'']]\n\nThe railway through Leicestershire is not electrified and therefore all services are operated by diesel trains. Plans to electrify this part of the line (as part of the wider [[Electric Spine]] project), announced in 2012<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.gov.uk/government/news/investing-in-rail-investing-in-jobs-and-growth|title= Investing in rail, investing in jobs and growth |date=16 July 2012 |publisher=Department for Transport}}</ref> and later resumed after a pause in 2015,<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.gov.uk/government/news/transpennine-and-midland-mainline-electrification-works-to-resume|title= TransPennine and Midland Mainline electrification works to resume |date=30 September 2015 |publisher=Department for Transport}}</ref> were cancelled in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/policy/single-view/view/sheffield-swansea-and-windermere-electrification-cancelled.html|title= Sheffield, Swansea and Windermere electrification cancelled|website=Railway Gazette|date=20 July 2017}}</ref> However, in February 2019 [[Andrew Jones (British politician)|Andrew Jones]], Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for Transport, announced that electrification would be extended northwards from Kettering up to Market Harborough, enabling the connection of the railway to a new power supply point at Braybrooke.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/news/uk/single-view/view/electrification-to-reach-market-harborough.html|title=Electrification to reach Market Harborough|website=Railway Gazette|date=5 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.railway-technology.com/news/uk-to-extend-electrification-of-midland-main-line|title=UK to extend electrification of Midland Main Line|website=Railway Technology|date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Service summary==\n{{rail start}}\n{{s-rail-national|previous=Leicester|next=St Pancras International|toc=East Midlands Railway|route=Midland Main Line|rowsmid=2|rows1=2}}\n{{s-rail-national|previous=Leicester|next=Kettering|toc=East Midlands Railway|route=Midland Main Line|hidemid=yes|hide1=yes}}\n{{Historical Rail Insert}}\n{{Rail line|previous=[[East Langton railway station|East Langton]]<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small> |next=[[Desborough railway station|Desborough and Rothwell]]<br /><small>Line open, station closed</small> |route=[[Midland Railway]]<br><small>[[Midland Main Line]]</small>|col={{MR colour}}}}\n{{Disused Rail Insert}}\n{{Rail line|previous=[[Lubenham railway station|Lubenham]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |next=[[Ashley and Weston railway station|Ashley and Weston]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route=[[London and North Western Railway]]<br><small>[[Rugby and Stamford Railway|Rugby to Peterborough East]]</small>|col={{LNWR colour}}}}\n{{Rail line|previous=[[Clipston and Oxendon railway station|Clipston and Oxendon]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |next=[[Hallaton railway station|Hallaton]]<br /><small>Line and station closed</small> |route=[[London and North Western Railway]]<br><small>Northampton to Nottingham</small>|col={{LNWR colour}}}}\n{{rail end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Market Harborough railway station}}\n{{stn art lnk|MHR|LE167QE}}\n\n{{Leicestershire and Rutland railway stations}}\n\n[[Category:Railway stations in Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:Former London and North Western Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Former Midland Railway stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 1850]]\n[[Category:Railway stations served by East Midlands Railway]]\n[[Category:Market Harborough]]\n[[Category:John William Livock buildings]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in Leicestershire]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed railway stations]]\n", "name_user": "Steamybrian2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMarket Harborough Line Speed Improvement project", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Market_Harborough_railway_station"}
{"title_page": "4mm Games", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| logo = 4mm Games logo.png\n| logo_size = 150px\n|name   = 4mm Games, LLC\n|type   = [[Limited liability company|LLC]]\n|foundation     = 2008<ref name=\"founded\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nycgameindustry.com/4mm-games/|title=4mm Games|publisher=NYC Game Industry|accessdate=2009-05-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090307010943/http://www.nycgameindustry.com/4mm-games|archive-date=2009-03-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|defunct        = 2012 <ref name=\"closure\">{{cite web|url= http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2012-05-15-4mm-games-from-start-up-to-shut-down |title=4mm Games: From Startup to Shutdown|author= Matt Martin|publisher=GamesIndustry.biz|date=2012-05-15|accessdate=2012-05-24}}</ref>\n\n|fate           = Dissolved <ref name=\"closure\" />\n|location       = [[New York City, New York]], United States\n|key_people     = Jamie King, Gary Foreman, Nicholas Perrett, Paul Coyne <ref name=\"key people\">Matt Martin (2009-08-26) [http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/4mm-games-nicholas-perrett \"4mm Games' Nicholas Perrett\"], [[GamesIndustry.biz]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref>\n|industry       = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n|products       = ''[[Def Jam Rapstar]]'',<ref name=\"defjam\">{{cite web|url=http://uk.xbox360.ign.com/articles/987/987307p1.html|title=Pre-E3 2009: Def Jam Rapstar Announced|author=Charles Onyett|publisher=IGN|date=2009-05-28|accessdate=2009-05-28| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090531121351/http://uk.xbox360.ign.com/articles/987/987307p1.html| archivedate= 31 May 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n<br />\nDog Show Friends,<ref name=\"dogs\" /> <br />\nAlli Skate <ref name=\"skate\" />\n}}\n'''4mm Games''' was a New York\u2013based video game development company founded in 2008<ref name=\"founded\" /> by two founders of [[Rockstar Games]], [[Jamie King]] and Gary Foreman along with former [[Image Metrics]] exec Nicholas Perrett, and [[Def Jam]] Enterprises, [[Warner Music Group]] and [[NBC]] executive Paul Coyne.<ref name=\"key people\" /> 4mm was founded with the intent of bringing the experience of Constantly Connected Gaming to the next generation of gamers.<ref name=\"intent\">Konami UK [http://uk.games.konami-europe.com/game.do?idGame=269 \"Def Jam Rapstar\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111154141/http://uk.games.konami-europe.com/game.do?idGame=269 |date=2011-01-11 }}, [[Konami]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref> [[OBE]] and former [[NCSoft]] CEO Geoff Heath was a member of the advisory board and offers strategic input.<ref name=\"heath\">Christopher Dring (2010-05-06) [http://www.mcvuk.com/news/38835/Heath-returns-with-4mm-Games \"Heath returns with 4mm Games\"], [[MCV (magazine)|MCV]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref>\n\nThe company released the [[Terminal Reality]] developed and [[Konami]] / [[Autumn Games]] published [[Hip-Hop Music]] game ''[[Def Jam Rapstar]]''<ref name=\"defjam\" /> on October 5, 2010, in North America<ref name=\"NA Launch\">Tom Magrino (2010-07-03) [http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/puzzle/defjamrapstar/news.html?sid=6264522 \"Def Jam Rapstar dropping in NA October 5\"], [[GameSpot]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref> and November 26, 2010, in Europe<ref name=\"EU Launch\">(2010-11-26) [http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/65821/MAKE_THE_WORLD_YOUR_STAGE_WITH_DEF_JAM_RAPSTAR.php \"MAKE THE WORLD YOUR STAGE WITH DEF JAM RAPSTAR\"], [[Gamasutra]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref> for the [[PlayStation 3]], [[Nintendo Wii]], and [[Xbox 360]].\n\n4mm Games also released Dog Show Friends, a [[Facebook]] social game based on The [[National Dog Show]] Presented by [[Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare Company|Purina]] in conjunction with [[NBC Sports]] on November 24, 2010.<ref name=\"dogs\">David Cohen (2010-11-24) [http://www.mediabistro.com/webnewser/nbc-sports-4mm-games-facebook-become-dog-show-friends_b9874 \"NBC Sports, 4mm Games, Facebook Become Dog Show Friends\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201040421/http://www.mediabistro.com/webnewser/nbc-sports-4mm-games-facebook-become-dog-show-friends_b9874 |date=2010-12-01 }}, [[GameSpot]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref>\n\nThe company was working with Alli, the Alliance of Action Sports to create new digital titles based on the organization's events. The plan was to release games based on sports such as snowboarding, skateboarding and motocross, as well as Alli tournaments such as the [[Dew Tour]], [[Gatorade|Gatorade Free Flow Tour]] and [[Winter Dew Tour]]. According to 4mm, the games would have provided both \u201cbite sized and fully immersive game play experiences\u201d and would be released on a range of platforms, including mobiles, Smartphones, TV and web browser.<ref name=\"alli\">James Batchelor (2010-06-11) [http://www.mcvuk.com/news/39415/4mm-to-enter-Action-Sports-market \"4mm to enter Action Sports market\"], [[MCV (magazine)|MCV]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref> The first of these games was to have been a free-to-play browser-based skateboarding game called Alli Skate.<ref name=\"skate\">Garrett Estrada (2010-10-21) [http://unlvrebelyell.com/2010/10/21/%E2%80%9C4mm%E2%80%9D-reveals-new-game-at-dew-tour-skate-finals/ \"4mm reveals new game at Dew Tour skate finals\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224062656/http://unlvrebelyell.com/2010/10/21/%E2%80%9C4mm%E2%80%9D-reveals-new-game-at-dew-tour-skate-finals/ |date=2010-12-24 }}, The Rebel Yell. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref>\n\n==Closure==\nThe release of [[Def Jam Rapstar]] was lukewarm and a year later the web portal burned through available funds and was closed without warning. 4mm founder Jamie King later stated in an interview that the problem was that they became too ambitious and that he wished they had \"either pushed the game back and made it for [[Kinect]] or [had it] come out a year earlier.\"<ref name=\"closure\" /> 4mm continued to work on other projects such as an experiment with UK game developer [[Jagex]]. However, on March 31, 2012, [[EMI|EMI Music Group]] filed a suit against 4mm and Terminal Reality. The suit claims that the game uses 54 unlicensed tracks that [[EMI]] values at $150,000 each.<ref name=\"emilawsuit\">{{cite web|url= http://www.joystiq.com/2012/03/31/emi-sues-def-jam-rapstar-creators/ |title=EMI sues Def Jam Rapstar creators|author=David Hinkle|publisher=Joystiq|date=2012-03-31|accessdate=2012-05-24}}</ref> On May 15, 2012, GameIndustry held an interview with King who stated that 4mm had run out of money and is on-hold. One of the reasons King cited was the ongoing lawsuit with EMI.<ref name=\"closure\" /> Two months later, [[City National Bank (California)|City National Bank]] sued [[Konami]] and Autumn Games for $8.9 million over a $15 million line of credit it approved for the game's development.<ref name=\"cnblawsuit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2012/05/24/konami-and-autumn-games-sued-for-fraud-over-15-million-def-jam/  |title=Konami and Autumn Games sued for fraud over $15 million Def Jam Rapstar loan|author=  Alexander Sliwinski|publisher=Joystiq|date=2012-05-24|accessdate=2012-05-24}}</ref> It is unclear what affect, if any, the CNB lawsuit will have on any potential future of 4mm.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090531092314/http://www.4mmgames.com/ Official website] (defunct)\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090605150414/http://www.defjamrapstar.com/ Def Jam Rapstar] (defunct)\n*[http://www.facebook.com/dogshowfriends Dog Show Friends]\n\n[[Category:Defunct video game companies]]\n[[Category:Video game companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Video game companies disestablished in 2012]]\n[[Category:Media companies based in New York City]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| logo = 4mm Games logo.png\n| logo