s founded with the intent of bringing the experience of Constantly Connected Gaming to the next generation of gamers.<ref name=\"intent\">Konami UK [http://uk.games.konami-europe.com/game.do?idGame=269 \"Def Jam Rapstar\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110111154141/http://uk.games.konami-europe.com/game.do?idGame=269 |date=2011-01-11 }}, [[Konami]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref> [[OBE]] and former [[NCSoft]] CEO Geoff Heath was a member of the advisory board and offers strategic input.<ref name=\"heath\">Christopher Dring (2010-05-06) [http://www.mcvuk.com/news/38835/Heath-returns-with-4mm-Games \"Heath returns with 4mm Games\"], [[MCV (magazine)|MCV]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref>\n\nThe company released the [[Terminal Reality]] developed and [[Konami]] / [[Autumn Games]] published [[Hip-Hop Music]] game ''[[Def Jam Rapstar]]''<ref name=\"defjam\" /> on October 5, 2010, in North America<ref name=\"NA Launch\">Tom Magrino (2010-07-03) [http://www.gamespot.com/xbox360/puzzle/defjamrapstar/news.html?sid=6264522 \"Def Jam Rapstar dropping in NA October 5\"], [[GameSpot]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref> and November 26, 2010, in Europe<ref name=\"EU Launch\">(2010-11-26) [http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/65821/MAKE_THE_WORLD_YOUR_STAGE_WITH_DEF_JAM_RAPSTAR.php \"MAKE THE WORLD YOUR STAGE WITH DEF JAM RAPSTAR\"], [[Gamasutra]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref> for the [[PlayStation 3]], [[Nintendo Wii]], and [[Xbox 360]].\n\n4mm Games also released Dog Show Friends, a [[Facebook]] social game based on The [[National Dog Show]] Presented by [[Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare Company|Purina]] in conjunction with [[NBC Sports]] on November 24, 2010.<ref name=\"dogs\">David Cohen (2010-11-24) [http://www.mediabistro.com/webnewser/nbc-sports-4mm-games-facebook-become-dog-show-friends_b9874 \"NBC Sports, 4mm Games, Facebook Become Dog Show Friends\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101201040421/http://www.mediabistro.com/webnewser/nbc-sports-4mm-games-facebook-become-dog-show-friends_b9874 |date=2010-12-01 }}, [[GameSpot]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref>\n\nThe company was working with Alli, the Alliance of Action Sports to create new digital titles based on the organization\u2019s events. The plan was to release games based on sports such as snowboarding, skateboarding and motocross, as well as Alli tournaments such as the [[Dew Tour]], [[Gatorade|Gatorade Free Flow Tour]] and [[Winter Dew Tour]]. According to 4mm, the games would have provided both \u201cbite sized and fully immersive game play experiences\u201d and would be released on a range of platforms, including mobiles, Smartphones, TV and web browser.<ref name=\"alli\">James Batchelor (2010-06-11) [http://www.mcvuk.com/news/39415/4mm-to-enter-Action-Sports-market \"4mm to enter Action Sports market\"], [[MCV (magazine)|MCV]]. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref> The first of these games was to have been a free-to-play browser-based skateboarding game called Alli Skate.<ref name=\"skate\">Garrett Estrada (2010-10-21) [http://unlvrebelyell.com/2010/10/21/%E2%80%9C4mm%E2%80%9D-reveals-new-game-at-dew-tour-skate-finals/ \"4mm reveals new game at Dew Tour skate finals\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101224062656/http://unlvrebelyell.com/2010/10/21/%E2%80%9C4mm%E2%80%9D-reveals-new-game-at-dew-tour-skate-finals/ |date=2010-12-24 }}, The Rebel Yell. Retrieved 2011-01-26.</ref>\n\n==Closure==\nThe release of [[Def Jam Rapstar]] was lukewarm and a year later the web portal burned through available funds and was closed without warning. 4mm founder Jamie King later stated in an interview that the problem was that they became too ambitious and that he wished they had \"either pushed the game back and made it for [[Kinect]] or [had it] come out a year earlier.\"<ref name=\"closure\" /> 4mm continued to work on other projects such as an experiment with UK game developer [[Jagex]]. However, on March 31, 2012, [[EMI|EMI Music Group]] filed a suit against 4mm and