16V''' DPF||2007||straight-4, [[Diesel engine|Diesel]]||1,248&nbsp;cc|| {{convert|55|kW|PS hp|0|abbr=on}}||113||13,0 s|| {{convert|102|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} ||{{convert|55.5|mpgus|L/100 km mpgimp|abbr=on}}\n|}\n\n===Chinese copy controversy===\n<gallery>\nFile:Great_Wall_Peri_China_2012-04-28.JPG|Great Wall Peri\nFile:Great_Wall_Peri_4x4.jpg|Great Wall Peri 4x4\n</gallery>\n\nIn December 2006, Fiat considered taking legal action against Chinese automaker [[Great Wall Motor]] for the company's [[Great Wall Peri|Peri]], which is a copy of the Panda's design.<ref>{{cite web|author=re |url=http://www.italiaspeed.com/2006/cars/financial/12/great_wall/1312.html |title=13.12.2006 FIAT IS CONSIDERING TAKING LEGAL ACTION TO STOP GREAT WALL'S PANDA CLONE BEING SOLD IN EUROPE |publisher=ItaliaSpeed.com |accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2008, Fiat successfully sued Great Wall and had the Peri banned from importation into Europe. In addition, the court order ruled for Great Wall to pay Fiat a 15,000 euro fine for the first Peri imported, and an additional 50,000 euros for every subsequent car that was imported.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.leftlanenews.com/fiat-successfully-sues-chinese-automaker-for-panda-clone.html |title=Fiat Successfully Sues Chinese Automaker for Panda Clone |publisher=Left Lane News |date=11 August 2010 |accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref>\n\nHowever, on October 2009, Great Wall Motor sued Fiat, accusing the latter of espionage. In the lawsuit, Great Wall claims that \"Fiat once instigated espionage to prowl into its research center and take photos of Peri small car that was still under developed.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.autoevolution.com/news/fiat-faces-lawsuit-from-great-wall-motor-co-11876.html |title=Fiat Faces Lawsuit from Great Wall Motor Co |publisher=Auto Evolution |date=19 August 2010 |accessdate=30 September 2010}}</ref>{{Clear}}\n\n==Third generation (2011\u2013present)==\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Third generation (319)\n| image = Fiat Panda in Mechelen NL.jpg\n| production = 2011\u2013present\n| assembly = [[Pomigliano d'Arco]], Italy\n| body_style = 5-door [[hatchback]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, front-wheel-drive]] or [[Front-engine, four-wheel-drive layout|four-wheel-drive]]\n| platform = [[Fiat Mini platform|FCA Mini]]\n| engine = {{unbulleted list | 1.0 L ''[[Twinair engine|TwinAir]]'' [[Straight-twin engine|I2]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]]) | 0.9 L ''[[Twinair engine|TwinAir Turbo]]'' I2 ([[turbocharger]] petrol) | 0.9 L ''[[Twinair engine|TwinAir Turbo]]'' I2 ([[turbocharger]] [[Compressed natural gas|CNG]]/petrol) | 1.2 L ''[[Fully Integrated Robotised Engine|FIRE]]'' I4 (petrol) | 1.2 L ''[[Fully Integrated Robotised Engine|FIRE]]'' [[Straight-4|I4]] ([[Liquefied petroleum gas|LPG]]/petrol) | 1.3 L ''[[Multijet]]'' I4 (turbocharged [[Diesel engine|diesel]])\n| '''[[Mild hybrid]]:'''\n| 1.0 L [[Fiat Global Small Engine|''GSE FireFly'']] [[Straight-three engine|I3]]\n}}\n| transmission = {{unbulleted list | 5-speed ''C514'' [[Manual transmission|manual]] | 5-speed ''C510 DS'' [[Manual transmission|manual]] | 6-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]] | 5-speed ''Dualogic'' [[Semi-automatic transmission|semi-automatic]]}}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2300|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|3653|-|3686|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1643|-|1672|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1551|-|1605|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{convert|940|-|1115|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| related = [[Lancia Ypsilon]]<br />[[Fiat 500 (2007)|Fiat 500]]<br />[[Fiat Uno#Novo Uno|Fiat Uno]]<br />[[Ford Ka]]\n| designer = Centro Stile Fiat\n}}\n[[File:2013 Fiat Panda Easy hatchback (2015-11-13) 02.jpg|thumb|left|Fiat Panda rear]]\nFiat presented the third generation of the Panda at the [[Frankfurt Motor Show|2011 Frankfurt Motor Show]] in September 2011. The new architecture is based on the [[Fiat Mini platform]]. The production began in the renewed [[Alfa Romeo Pomigliano d'Arco Plant|Pomigliano d'Arco Plant]] in the last quarter of 2011.\n\nThe older model stayed in production and was sold as Panda Classic, remaining popular thanks to its lower pricing (about 27%). The decision to manufacture the car in Italy, instead of manufacturing it with the cheaper workforce in Tychy, Poland, was taken because of the agreement between Italian Prime Minister [[Mario Monti]] and Fiat directors not to close down any of Fiat's plants in Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://finanse.wp.pl/kat,104596,title,Fiat-Panda-odjezdza-z-Polski,wid,15048426,wiadomosc.html |title=Fiat Panda odje\u017cd\u017ca z Polski! - Finanse - WP.PL |publisher=Finanse |date= |accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Models===\n\n====Panda Natural Power====\nThe Natural Power is the [[CNG]]/[[petrol]] [[bi-fuel]] version of the Panda. Unlike the previous generation - which adopted a 70 PS 1.4 ''[[Fully Integrated Robotised Engine|FIRE]]'' inline four - it is powered by the turbocharged, 0.9 liter, two-cylinder ''[[Twinair engine|TwinAir]]'' engine. The system is developed in-house and factory installed.<ref name=\"fiatpress models\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fiatpress.com/press/article/115322|title=The Fiat Panda is available in four versions: 4x4, Trekking, Natural Power and EasyPower|date= 16 October 2012|website= FGA EMEA Press site|type= press release|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe CNG is stored in two - one 22 L and one 50 L - [[gas cylinders]]: the former housed longitudinally in the [[transmission tunnel]], the latter transversally behind the rear axle. Due to the cylinders being both located under the [[floorpan]], the boot's volume is reduced only by 25 liters - 200 L instead of the monofuel's 225. On the other hand, this requires a 40&nbsp;mm taller ride height and a reworked, transversal [[Muffler|silencer]] - thus the Natural Power uses the lifted chassis of the Trekking / 4x4 versions.\n\nTotal bi-fuel capacity is 72 liters - or 12 kilograms - of CNG and 35 L of petrol - two liters less than the monofuel's 37.\nAt startup the engine runs on petrol, but switches to CNG immediately after; the car switches back to petrol automatically if it runs out of CNG or any time by driver's demand, via a dedicated button on the dashboard.<ref name=\"fiatpress models\" />\n\nDue to the new tightening emissions regulations Euro 6d-Temp, after September 2018 the power output of the Natural Power ''[[Twinair engine|TwinAir]]'' engine is reduced from 80 to 70 PS, when running on CNG - although remains 85 PS, when running on petrol.\n\n====Panda EasyPower====\nThe EasyPower is the [[Liquefied petroleum gas|LPG]]/petrol bi-fuel version of the Panda; like the Natural Power it too is factory developed and manufactured.\nIts 1.2 ''FIRE'' inline four develops 69 PS.<ref name=\"fiatpress models\" />\n\n====Panda Trekking====\nLaunched in late 2012, the Trekking is a two-wheel drive model offering the looks and features of the Panda 4x4. It is distinguished from the 4x4, by the absence of skid plate inserts on bumpers, no \"4x4\" inlay in the bodyside molding and alloy wheels painted silver instead of a darker grey.\n\nAvailable on this model are the 0.9 ''TwinAir'' turbocharged petrol and 1.3 ''Multijet II'' turbodiesel engines, with some offroad capabilities thanks to the \"Traction +\" ESC-based electronically simulated front [[locking differential]]<ref name=\"fiatpress models\" /> and the standard [[M+S|M+S tires]], along with the ''TwinAir Natural Power'' turbocharged petrol/methane engine without the latter capabilities.\n\nThe Panda Trekking stayed in production until late 2016.\n\n[[File:' 12 - ITALY - Fiat Panda 4x4 Off-road test drive - Motorshow di Bologna cut.JPG|thumb|left|200px|A Panda 4x4 in action]]\n\n====Panda 4x4====\nThe third generation all wheel drive Panda was introduced at the 2012 [[Paris Motor Show]].<ref name=\"Panda\">{{cite web|url=http://www.italiaspeed.com/2012/cars/fiat/08/panda_4x4/2908.html|title=Panda 4x4|accessdate=3 September 2012|work=italiaspeed.com}}</ref> The engine lineup includes the ''TwinAir'' turbocharged petrol engine and ''Multijet II'' turbodiesel. The TwinAir engine is linked to a six-speed transmission with a short ratio first gear and the Diesel is linked to a 5-speed transmission.<ref name=\"fiatpress 4x4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fiatpress.com/press/article/115248|title=Fiat Panda 4x4 debuts in world preview at the Paris Motor Show|date= 29 August 2012|website= FGA EMEA Press site|type= press release|accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Panda 4x4 receives model specific bumpers with extra cladding, body side moldings, plastic wheelarch extensions and 175/65 M+S tires on 15\" dark grey alloy wheels.\nThe full-time all wheel drive system is composed by two open [[Differential (mechanical device)|differentials]] front and rear and a rear-mounted electronically controlled coupling, which sends torque to the two axles in proportion depending on road conditions.<ref name=\"Milner\">{{cite web|title=The Fiat Panda 4x4 Is Back|url=http://www.milneroffroad.com/blog/4x4-fiat-panda-back/|website=Milner Off Road Blog}}</ref>\nAt the rear is a specially developed [[torsion beam]] semi-independent suspension, a change from the previous generation's [[trailing arm]]s.\n\nAn electronically simulated locking differential (termed ''ELD'', ''Electronic Locking Differential'') supplements the open-type differentials. The ELD works automatically by braking the wheel(s) where the ESC sensors detect excessive wheel slip, thus making the differentials more torque to the wheels in better traction conditions; this functionality is useful on low-grip surfaces, and is activated by the driver via a console switch.<ref name=\"fiatpress 4x4\" />\n{{Multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | width =\n| image1   = 2015 Fiat Panda Cross TwinAir 900cc Front.jpg\n| image2   = 2015 Fiat Panda Cross TwinAir 900cc Rear.jpg\n| caption2 = Fiat Panda Cross\n}}\n\n====Panda Cross====\nLaunched at the 2014 [[Geneva Motor Show]], it is the range topping, offroad-styled Panda. Mechanically it is based on the Panda 4x4, offering the same choice of powertrains.\nAs in the previous generation the Cross is recognizable by its wider 185/65 tyres on specific alloy wheels, new fascias with prominent skid plates and unique broken up head- and taillights arrangement. The new bumpers, together with an increased [[ground clearance]], give the car better [[approach and departure angles]].<ref name=\"fiatpress Cross\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fiatpress.com/press/article/115928|title=2014 Geneva Motor Show: d\u00e9but of the Fiat Panda Cross and Fiat Freemont Cross|date= 18 February 2014|website= FGA EMEA Press site|type= press release|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Panda Hybrid====\nIn 2020, Fiat updated the Panda with mild-hybrid technology. It's a combination of a 1.0-litre 3-cylinder FireFly petrol engine, a 12-volt BSG (Belt-integrated Starter Generator) electric motor and a 11 Ah lithium-ion battery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.autodevot.com/2020/04/fiat-500-and-panda-cross-get-updated-mild-hybrid-technology/|title=Fiat 500 and Panda get updated with mild-hybrid technology|website=www.autodevot.com|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Special editions===\n\n====Panda 4x4 Steyr====\nAustrian market only special edition, announced in 2012. Its [[Steyr Tractor]] theme celebrates the several collaborations throughout the years between Fiat and former [[Steyr-Daimler-Puch]], such as the development of the original Panda's four wheel drive system.\nBuilt on the basis of the Panda 4x4 1.3 ''Multijet II'' with richer interior standard equipment, it was available in red or white with contrasting colour side stripes and Steyr logo decals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiatpress.at/press/article/254|title=Fiat Panda 4x4 Steyr|date= 1 October 2012|website= FGA EMEA Press site|type= press release|language= German|accessdate=27 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Panda 4x4 Antarctica====\nThis limited, 200 cars edition was premiered at the 2013 [[Frankfurt Motor Show]], commemorating the 30th anniversary of the Panda 4x4.\nIt was too based on the Panda 4x4 1.3 ''Multijet II'', featuring several normally extra cost options like [[climate control|automatic climate control]], [[parking sensors]] and Blue&Me [[Bluetooth]] connectivity as standard. The exterior was characterized by a white with black roof two-tone paint scheme accented by orange wheel centers and side mirror caps.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiatpress.com/press/article/115809|title=Panda 4x4 Antartica together with the symbol of the South Pole|date= 21 October 2014|website= FGA EMEA Press site|type= press release|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref>\n{{Euro NCAP |year=2011 |overall_stars=4 |description=Fiat Panda |reference={{cite web |title=Official Fiat Panda 2011 safety rating results |url=https://www.euroncap.com/en/results/fiat/panda/10970 |website=Euro NCAP}} |adult_points=30 |adult_percent=80 |child_points=31 |child_percent=63 |pedestrian_points=18 |pedestrian_percent=49 |safety_points=3 |safety_percent=43 |align=right}}\n{{Euro NCAP |year=2018 |overall_stars=0 |description=FIAT Panda |reference={{cite web|url=https://www.euroncap.com/en/results/fiat/panda/34191|title=Official FIAT Panda safety rating|accessdate=27 February 2019}} |adult_points=17.4 |adult_percent=45 |child_points=8 |child_percent=16 |pedestrian_points=22.9 |pedestrian_percent=47 |safety_points=1 |safety_percent=7 |align=right}}\n\n===Safety===\nThe third generation Panda was tested by [[Euro NCAP]] towards the end of 2011, and achieved a four star result. One star was dropped mainly because the Panda's [[electronic stability control]] wasn't available on all trim levels, such as the one of the tested car. Fiat clarified on the same day that ESC would be offered on the entire Fiat Panda range in the first months of 2012.<ref name=\"fiatpress11345\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fiatpress.com/press/article/11345|title=Fiat Panda EuroNCAP result|date= 23 November 2011|website= FGA EMEA Press site|type= press release|accessdate=24 November 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Collision avoidance system====\n{{main|Collision avoidance system#Fiat|l1=Fiat City Brake Control}}\nFiat's ''City Brake Control'' low-speed crash avoidance system is available as optional on the Panda.\nThe system works by readying and if necessary automatically executing an emergency stop whenever an imminent collision is detected by its [[Lidar|laser sensor]].<ref name=\"fiatpress115664\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fiatpress.com/press/article/115664|title=City Brake Control wins the \u2018Euro NCAP Advanced\u2019 award |date= 26 June 2013|website= FGA EMEA Press site|type= press release|accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref> In 2013 City Brake Control attained the [[Euro NCAP#Euro NCAP Advanced|Euro NCAP Advanced]] reward.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euroncap.com/rewards/fiat_cbc.aspx|title=Euro NCAP Advanced: FIAT City Brake Control|website= Euro NCAP official site|accessdate=30 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Records===\nAt 5:28pm on Monday 11 February 2013, Philip Young and Paul Brace broke the world record drive, in either direction, from Cape Town in South Africa to London in Great Britain with a Fiat Panda two-cylinder 0.9 TwinAir. The drive started on 1 February and ended 10 days, 13 hours and 28 minutes later, shaving over a day off the previous record, achieved in 1983 by a [[Land Rover Defender]] two years earlier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.africarecordrun.com/ |title=Fiat Panda World Record Attempt |publisher=Africa Record Run |date=8 October 2012 |accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref>{{What?|reason=In 1983 two years earlier?|date=July 2017}}\n\n===Awards===\n* Panda 4x4: [[Top Gear (magazine)|Top Gear Magazine's]] \"SUV of the Year 2012\".<ref name=tg>{{cite web|title=SUV of the Year: Fiat Panda 4x4|url=http://www.topgear.com/uk/car-news/top-gear-awards-suv-of-the-year-2012-12-19|work=topgear.com|accessdate=3 February 2013}}</ref>\n* Panda TwinAir Turbo Natural Power: \"Das gr\u00fcnste Auto der Schweiz 2013\" (\"Greenest car in Switzerland\"), part of Swiss Car of the Year 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fiatpress.com/press/article/115371|title=Panda TwinAir Turbo Natural Power earns title of 'Most eco-friendly car' of 2013 in Switzerland|date= 23 November 2012|website= FGA EMEA Press site|type= press release|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.schweizer-illustrierte.ch/lifestyle/das-sind-die-gewinner|title=Schweizer Auto des Jahres, Das sind die Gewinner|date= 23 November 2012|website= schweizer-illustrierte.com|accessdate=18 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Engines===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! Engine\n! Year of introduction\n! Type\n! Displacement\n! Power at rpm\n! Torque at rpm\n! [[CO2|CO<sub>2</sub>]]/km\n! {{convert|0|\u2013|100|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n! Top speed\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n|'''1.0 TwinAir'''||2011,<br />from launch||straight-2, [[Petrol engine|petrol]]||964&nbsp;cc||{{convert|60|PS|kW hp||abbr=on}} at 6,250||{{convert|88|Nm|lbft|abbr=on}} at 3,500||99&nbsp;g/km||15,7 s|| {{convert|159|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n|'''0.9 TwinAir Turbo'''||2011,<br />from launch||straight-2, petrol||875&nbsp;cc||{{convert|85|PS|kW hp||abbr=on}} at 5,500||{{convert|145|Nm|lbft|abbr=on}} at 1,900||99&nbsp;g/km||11,2 s|| {{convert|177|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n|'''0.9 TwinAir Turbo Dualogic'''||2011,<br />from launch||straight-2, petrol||875&nbsp;cc||{{convert|78|PS|kW hp||abbr=on}} at 5,500||{{convert|100|Nm|lbft|abbr=on}} at 2,000||95&nbsp;g/km||11,2 s|| {{convert|177|km/h|mi/h|abbr=on}}\n|- style=\"background:#fff;\"\n|'''1.2 Fire 8v'''||2011,<br />from launch||straight-4, petrol||1,242&nbsp;cc||{{convert|69|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,500||{{convert|102|Nm|lbft|abbr=on}} at 3,000||120&nbsp;g/km||14,2 s