sian Empire at the 1912 Summer Olympics|1912]], [[Soviet Union at the 1952 Summer Olympics|1952]]\u2014[[Soviet Union at the 1980 Summer Olympics|1980]], [[Soviet Union at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988]]\u2013present) has won 589 gold and 1,556 total medals.\n\n===Winter Olympics===\nMedal totals of the [[Soviet Union at the Olympics|Soviet Union]]/[[Unified Team at the Olympics|Unified Team]]/[[Russia at the Olympics|Russia]]/[[Olympic Athletes from Russia at the 2018 Winter Olympics|Olympic Athletes from Russia]]<ref name=\"auto1\"/><ref name=\"auto2\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/> and the [[United States at the Olympics|United States]]<ref name=\"auto3\"/> since [[1956 Winter Olympics medal table|1956]], when the Soviet Union started to compete.\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%;\"\n! colspan=8|{{Flagicon|Russia}} [[Russia]]\n|-\n!Games\n|style=\"background:gold; width:3.2em; font-weight:bold;\"|Gold\n|style=\"background:silver; width:3.7em; font-weight:bold;\"|Silver\n| style=\"background:#c96; width:3.7em; font-weight:bold;\"|Bronze\n!style=\"width:3.5em; font-weight:bold;\"|Total\n!style=\"width:4em; font-weight:bold;\"|[[Olympic medal table|Rank]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1956}} || 7 || 3 || 6 || 16 || bgcolor=F7F6A8| [[1956 Winter Olympics medal table|1]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1960}} || 7 || 5 || 9 || 21 || bgcolor=F7F6A8| [[1960 Winter Olympics medal table|1]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1964}} || 11 || 8 || 6 || 25 || bgcolor=F7F6A8| [[1964 Winter Olympics medal table|1]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1968}} || 5 || 5 || 3 || 13 || bgcolor=DCE5E5| [[1968 Winter Olympics medal table|2]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1972}} || 8 || 5 || 3 || 16 || bgcolor=F7F6A8| [[1972 Winter Olympics medal table|1]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1976}} || 13 || 6 || 8 || 27 || bgcolor=F7F6A8| [[1976 Winter Olympics medal table|1]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1980}} || 10 || 6 || 6 || 22 || bgcolor=F7F6A8| [[1980 Winter Olympics medal table|1]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1984}} || 6 || 10 || 9 || 25 || bgcolor=DCE5E5| [[1984 Winter Olympics medal table|2]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1988}} || 11 || 9 || 9 || 29 || bgcolor=F7F6A8| [[1988 Winter Olympics medal table|1]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1992}} || 9 || 6 || 8 || 23 || bgcolor=DCE5E5| [[1992 Winter Olympics medal table|2]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1994}} || 11 || 8 || 4 || 23 || bgcolor=F7F6A8| [[1994 Winter Olympics medal table|1]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1998}} || 9 || 6 || 3 || 18 || bgcolor=ffdab9| [[1998 Winter Olympics medal table|3]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2002}} || 5 || 4 || 4 || 13 || [[2002 Winter Olympics medal table|5]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2006}} || 8 || 6 || 8 || 22 || [[2006 Winter Olympics medal table|4]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2010}} || 3 || 5 || 7 || 15 || [[2010 Winter Olympics medal table|11]]\n|- \n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2014}} || 11 || 9 || 9 || 29 || bgcolor=F7F6A8| [[2014 Winter Olympics medal table|1]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2018}} || 2 || 6 || 9 || 17 || [[2018 Winter Olympics medal table|13]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2022}} || colspan=8 |''Future event''\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2026}} || colspan=8 |''Future event''\n|-\n! Total !! 136 !! 107 !! 111 !! 354 || [[All-time Olympic Games medal table|2]]\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:90%;\"\n! colspan=8|{{Flagicon|United States}} [[United States]]\n|-\n!Games\n|style=\"background:gold; width:3.2em; font-weight:bold;\"|Gold\n|style=\"background:silver; width:3.7em; font-weight:bold;\"|Silver\n| style=\"background:#c96; width:3.7em; font-weight:bold;\"|Bronze\n!style=\"width:3.5em; font-weight:bold;\"|Total\n!style=\"width:4em; font-weight:bold;\"|[[Olympic medal table|Rank]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1956}} || 2 || 3 || 2 || 7 || [[1956 Winter Olympics medal table|6]]\n|- \n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1960}} || 3 || 4 || 3 || 10 || style=\"background:#ffdab9;\"|[[1960 Winter Olympics medal table|3]] \n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1964}} || 1 || 2 || 4 || 7 || [[1964 Winter Olympics medal table|8]] \n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1968}} || 1 || 5 || 1 || 7 || [[1968 Winter Olympics medal table|9]] \n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1972}} || 3 || 2 || 3 || 8 || [[1972 Winter Olympics medal table|5]] \n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1976}} || 3 || 3 || 4 || 10 || style=\"background:#ffdab9;\"|[[1976 Winter Olympics medal table|3]] \n|- \n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1980}} || 6 || 4 || 2 || 12 || style=\"background:#ffdab9;\"|[[1980 Winter Olympics medal table|3]] \n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1984}} || 4 || 4 || 0 || 8 || style=\"background:#ffdab9;\"|[[1984 Winter Olympics medal table|3]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1988}} || 2 || 1 || 3 || 6 || [[1988 Winter Olympics medal table|9]] \n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1992}} || 5 || 4 || 2 || 11 || [[1992 Winter Olympics medal table|5]] \n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1994}} || 6 || 5 || 2 || 13 || [[1994 Winter Olympics medal table|5]] \n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|1998}} || 6 || 3 || 4 || 13 || [[1998 Winter Olympics medal table|5]] \n|- \n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2002}} || 10 || 13 || 11 || 34 || style=\"background:#ffdab9;\"|[[2002 Winter Olympics medal table|3]]\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2006}} || 9 || 9 || 7 || 25 || style=\"background:#dce5e5;\"|[[2006 Winter Olympics medal table|2]] \n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2010}} || 9 || 15 || 13 || 37 || style=\"background:#ffdab9;\"|[[2010 Winter Olympics medal table|3]] \n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2014}} || 9 || 9 || 10 || 28 || [[2014 Winter Olympics medal table|4]] \n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2018}} || 9 || 8 || 6 || 23 || |[[2018 Winter Olympics medal table|4]] \n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2022}} || colspan=8 |''Future event''\n|-\n|align=left| {{GamesName|WOG|2026}} || colspan=8 |''Future event''\n|-\n! Total !! 88 !! 94 !! 77 !! 259 || [[All-time Olympic Games medal table|4]]\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\nOverall, the United States ([[United States at the 1924 Winter Olympics|1924]]\u2013present) has won 105 gold and 305 total medals, and Russia ([[Soviet Union at the 1956 Winter Olympics|1956]]\u2013present) has won 136 gold and 354 total medals.\n\n===Basketball===\n{{see also|1972 Olympic Men's Basketball Final}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:USA USSR 1972 basketball match.jpeg|350px|thumb|right|(On the left) American players celebrating their apparent victory only to be told that the final three seconds of the game would be replayed for the third time. (On the right) Soviet players scoring after the final three seconds were replayed for the third time.]] -->\n[[File:AudiDomeFCB.jpg|thumb|upright|300px|Inside view (in 2014) of the [[Rudi-Sedlmayer-Halle]], where the final was played]]\nThe United States and Soviet Union sporting adversary reached its peak during the [[Cold war]]. The U.S. men's team was considered a favorite in the run-up to the 1972 Games. Since the first Olympic basketball tournament at the [[Basketball at the 1936 Summer Olympics|1936 Olympics]] in [[Berlin]], the Americans haven't lost a single game, winning seven consecutive gold medals in a dominating fashion. Their record reached an unprecedented 63-0 before the final game. Since the [[Basketball at the 1952 Summer Olympics|1952 tournament]] the Soviet team challenged the Americans, winning silver in 1952, [[Basketball at the 1956 Summer Olympics|1956]], [[Basketball at the 1960 Summer Olympics|1960]], [[Basketball at the 1964 Summer Olympics|1964]] and bronze in [[Basketball at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968]]. Outside of the Olympics, the Soviets had already defeated the U.S. team in the [[FIBA World Cup|World Championship]] play. However, the Americans never sent their best collegiate players to that tournament. \n\nIt is important to note that the Olympics strictly prohibited any involvement of professional athletes at the time. The Soviet Union and other [[Eastern Bloc]] countries used that rule to their advantage, listing all its top players as soldiers or workers what allowed them to breach the amateur rules. Western experts classified these athletes as professionals.<ref name=\"a1972\">{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/classic/s/Classic_1972_usa_ussr_gold_medal_hoop.html|title=Classic 1972 USA vs. USSR Basketball game|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=August 6, 2004|accessdate=April 13, 2009}}</ref> On the other hand, leading American players were unable to play in the Olympics as they were officially professional and played in the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]. That disadvantage hadn't prevented the Americans from winning the first seven Olympic basketball tournaments without a single defeat.\n\nThe confrontation of the Soviet Union and United States on the [[basketball court]] was deeply connected to the confrontation on the political front. Many American viewers assumed that 1972 Games were openly [[Anti-Americanism|anti-American]].<ref name=espn1>''By Frank Saraceno''. [http://espn.go.com/classic/s/Classic_1972_usa_ussr_gold_medal_hoop.html Classic 1972 USA vs. USSR Basketball game.] // espn.go.com (August 6, 2004)</ref> There were rumors that the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union|Communist party]] had bribed the officials because they wanted the USSR to win 50 gold medals at these Olympics in commemoration of the 50th anniversary of the Soviet Union.<ref name=joursport1>''Chris Elzey (American Studies Purdue University)''. [http://www.la84foundation.org/SportsLibrary/JSH/JSH2002/JSH2903/jsh2903ag.pdf \u00ab03 Seconds From Gold\u00bb (2002).] \u00abJournal of Sports History\u00bb (vol 29, issue 3, page 518\u2014522) // la84foundation.org</ref>\n\nThe [[1972 United States men's Olympic basketball team|United States team]] was the youngest in history. American players usually participated in the Olympics once before turning pro, and the U.S. team always had new players every four years. The 1972 team didn't have a clear leader. A rising star [[Bill Walton]] declined an invitation to participate. Nevertheless, the team was heavily favored featuring such players as [[Doug Collins (basketball)|Doug Collins]] or [[Tommy Burleson]] (the tallest player among all teams).\n\nThe young American team was confronted by a veteran Soviet team, featuring stars [[Sergei Belov]], [[Modestas Paulauskas]], and [[Alexander Belov]]. The players had played together for more than seven years. For [[Gennadi Volnov]] it was the fourth Olympic appearance.\n\nThe Soviets performed strongly at the beginning, winning the first half 26:21. The Soviets kept the Americans 4\u20138 points behind during the first half.\n\nIn the second half Soviets targeted [[Dwight Jones (basketball)|Dwight Jones]], as they considered him the leader of the U.S. team. On the 28th minute he was provoked by [[Mikheil Korkia]] and responded. Both players were sent off. The Soviets were satisfied, as they deemed Korkia less significant for them than Jones for the Americans. The next minute Alexander Belov hit [[Jim Brewer (basketball)|Jim Brewer]] during the free-throw, and Brewer was unable to continue playing. According to the Americans, the referees did not notice the foul.\n\nWith 10 minutes left, the Soviets increased their lead to 10 points. After that Americans finally started to press the Soviets. It helped them to cut the deficit to 1 point. Soviet players started to feel nervous. With less than a minute left, [[Doug Collins (basketball)|Doug Collins]] stole a Soviet pass at halfcourt and was fouled hard by [[Zurab Sakandelidze]] as he drove toward the basket, being knocked down into the basket stanchion. With three seconds remaining on the game clock, Collins was awarded two free throws and sank the first to tie the score at 49. Just as Collins lifted the ball to begin his shooting motion in attempting the second free throw, the horn from the scorer's table sounded, marking the beginning of a chain of events that left the game's final three seconds mired in controversy. Although the unexpected sound of the horn caused lead referee [[Renato Righetto]] to turn away from the free throw attempt and look over to the scorer's table, play was not stopped. Collins never broke his shooting motion and continued with his second free throw, scoring to put the U.S. ahead by a score of 50:49. Immediately following Collins' free throws, the Soviets inbounded the ball and failed to score. Soviet coaches claimed that they had requested a timeout before Collins' foul shots. The referees ordered the clock reset to three seconds and the game's final seconds replayed. The horn sounded as a length-of-the-court Soviet pass was being released from the inbounding player, the pass missed its mark, and the American players began celebrating. Nevertheless, final three seconds were replayed for a third time. This time, the Soviets' [[Alexander Belov]] and the USA's [[Kevin Joyce (basketball)|Kevin Joyce]] and [[James Forbes (basketball)|Jim Forbes]] went up for the pass, and Belov caught the long pass from Ivan Edeshko near the American basket. Belov then laid the ball in for the winning points as the buzzer sounded.\n\nThe Americans regained the basketball crown in [[Basketball at the 1976 Summer Olympics|1976]], but their ability to stay competitive with college players against seasoned professionals from the Soviet Union was decreasing. In [[Basketball at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988]], the Soviets beat the United States once again, eliminating them in the semifinals. That game was a turning point in international basketball, as [[FIBA]] officials started to realize that amateur rules were extremely unfair. In 1989, NBA players were finally allowed in the Olympics.\n\n===Ice hockey===\n{{see also|Miracle on Ice}}\n[[File:USA - Soviet Union 1980 match.jpg|thumb|upright|300px|An amateur photo featuring U.S. vs USSR matchup]]\nThe 1980 hockey game between the U.S. and USSR was dubbed the \"[[Miracle on Ice]]\", when American college players defeated the heavily favored seasoned professionals from the [[Soviet Union national ice hockey team|Soviet Union]] on the way to a gold medal at the [[Ice hockey at the 1980 Winter Olympics|Winter Olympics]] in [[Lake Placid, New York|Lake Placid]], [[New York (state)|New York]]. The Soviet Union had won the gold medal in five of the six previous Winter Olympic Games, and were the favorites to win once more. Though ice hockey is not a major sport in most areas of the United States, the \"Miracle\" is often listed as one of the all-time greatest American sporting achievements. The U.S. also won the gold medal in the [[Ice hockey at the 1960 Winter Olympics|1960 Games]] at [[Squaw Valley, Placer County, California|Squaw Valley]], [[California]], defeating the Soviet Union, [[Canada men's national ice hockey team|Canada]], [[Czechoslovakia men's national ice hockey team|Czechoslovakia]], and [[Sweden men's national ice hockey team|Sweden]] along the way. However, since this victory is not as well known as the 1980 win, it has come to be known as the \"Forgotten Miracle\".<ref>{{cite web|last=Burnside|first=Scott|title=Hockey's miracle before the 'Miracle'|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/olympics/winter/2010/icehockey/columns/story?columnist=burnside_scott&id=4897805|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=February 8, 2010|accessdate=October 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Morning Skate: The Forgotten Miracle of 1960|url=http://slapshot.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/12/11/the-morning-skate-the-forgotten-miracle-of-1960/|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 11, 2009|accessdate=October 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe U.S. and the Soviet Union next met at the Olympics in [[Ice hockey at the 1988 Winter Olympics|1988]]. As in 1980, the Soviets were represented by their star-studded veterans, while the Americans fielded a team of college players. The Soviets won the encounter 7\u20135 and went on to win the gold medal, while the U.S. placed seventh.\n\nThe two teams met again at the [[Ice hockey at the 1992 Winter Olympics|1992 Olympics]] in a semi-final match. There, the Unified Team (the successor to the Soviet Union) won 5\u20132. While some stars had left the Soviet Union to play in the NHL, the Unified Team still boasted many veterans from their domestic professional league, while the Americans were represented primarily by college players. The Unified Team eventually won the gold medal, while the U.S. placed fourth.\n\nThe U.S. and Russia (the successor to the Unified Team) met twice at the [[1996 World Cup of Hockey]]. The Americans won both games 5-2 en route to the tournament championship.\n\nThe U.S., coached by Herb Brooks, and Russia, coached by [[Viacheslav Fetisov|Slava Fetisov]], met twice in the [[Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics|2002 Winter Olympics]] in Salt Lake City, which included a 2\u20132 round-robin draw and a 3\u20132 semi-final win for the Americans. The semi-final match was played 22 years to the day after the \"Miracle on Ice\" game.<ref name=\"sportsillustrated.cnn.com\"/> The U.S. eventually won silver, while Russia won bronze.\n\nThe two teams met in the quarterfinals of the [[2004 World Cup of Hockey]], with the U.S. earning a decisive 5-3 victory.\n\nThe U.S. and Russia played each other in a round-robin game at the [[Ice hockey at the 2014 Winter Olympics|2014 Winter Olympics]] in Sochi. The game was tied 2\u20132 after overtime before the Americans prevailed in an eight-round shootout, with [[T.J. Oshie]] scoring on 4 of 6 attempts for the United States. The match has been dubbed by some as the \"Marathon on Ice\" due to its length.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.teamusa.org:443/Road-to-Sochi-2014/Features/2014/February/15/Team-USA-Beats-Russia-In-Marathon-On-Ice|title=Team USA Beats Russia In 'Marathon On Ice'|website=Team USA}}</ref> Both teams, however, failed to medal; the Americans finished fourth (losing in the semis to Canada and to Finland in the bronze medal game), while the Russians placed fifth (losing to Finland in the quarterfinals).\n\n==See also==\n*[[United States at the Summer Olympics]]\n*[[United States at the Winter Olympics]]\n*[[List of United States Olympic medalists]]\n*[[United States at the Paralympics]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |title=United States of America |publisher=International Olympic Committee |url=http://www.olympic.org/united-states-of-america }}\n* {{IOC medals|NOC=USA}}\n* {{cite web |title=Olympic Medal Winners |publisher=International Olympic Committee |url=http://www.olympic.org/athletes?search=1&countryname=united%20states%20of%20america }}\n* {{cite web |title=United States |publisher=Sports-Reference.com |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/countries/USA }}\n\n{{country at games navbox|United States|Olympics}}\n{{Nations at the Olympics}}\n{{National sports teams of the United States}}\n{{Sport in the United States}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:United States At The Olympics}}\n[[Category:United States at the Olympics| ]]\n[[Category:National sports teams of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Spdslecturer", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_at_the_Olympics"}
{"title_page": "Askam and Ireleth", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                England     \n|coordinates = {{coord|54.189|-3.204|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name=           Askam and Ireleth \n|civil_parish=            Askam and Ireleth\n|population =             3632\n|population_ref=          (2001)<ref name=\"Population\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/642/1752/1754/3837712243.xls|title=Cumbria population figures|accessdate=9 March 2007|year=2001|format=XLS|work=2001 census|publisher=Cumbria County Council|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010203/http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/642/1752/1754/3837712243.xls|archivedate=27 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|shire_district=          [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow-in-Furness]]\n|region=                  North West England\n|shire_county=            [[Cumbria]]\n|constituency_westminster=[[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness]]\n|post_town=               ASKAM-IN-FURNESS\n|postcode_district=       LA16\n|postcode_area=           LA \n|dial_code=               01229\n|os_grid_reference=       SD214777\n|static_image_name=       Askamandirelethlogo.jpg\n|static_image_alt=        Logo of the carish council on a rubbish bin.\n|static_image_caption=    The parish council logo. The roundel includes the initials of the villages on a symbolic representation of the beach, sea and fells.\n}}\n'''Askam and Ireleth''' is a [[civil parish]] close to [[Barrow-in-Furness]] in the county of Cumbria, in [[North West England]]. [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] part of [[Lancashire]], it originally consisted of two separate coastal villages with different origins and histories which, in recent times, have merged to become one continuous settlement. The population of the civil parish taken at the 2011 Census was 3,632.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11120167&c=Askam&d=16&e=62&g=6411250&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1453734226319&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIreleth has its origins as a [[mediaeval]] farming village clustered on the hillside overlooking the flat sands of the [[Duddon Estuary]].<ref name=\"A Short History\">{{cite web|accessdate=9 March 2007|publisher=Mark Maclean|url=http://users.hunterlink.net.au/~mbemdm/Ireleth_Askam_history.pdf|title=A Short History of Ireleth and Askam-in-Furness|last=Maclean|first=Mark|year=1997|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927025046/http://users.hunterlink.net.au/~mbemdm/Ireleth_Askam_history.pdf|archive-date=27 September 2007|url-status = dead}}</ref> Askam was established following the discovery of large quantities of iron ore near the village in the middle of the 18th century.\n\nThe pair originally fell within the boundaries of the [[Lonsdale (hundred)|Hundred of Lonsdale]] 'north of the sands' in the [[Historic counties of England|historic county]] of [[Lancashire]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043 |title=Lancashire AncC: Historical Boundaries |accessdate=9 March 2007 |publisher=A Vision of Britain Through Time |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001001412/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043 |archivedate=1 October 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy }}</ref> but following [[Local Government Act 1972|local government reforms]] in 1974 became part of the county of [[Cumbria]], along with the rest of [[Furness]].\n\nThe nearby [[River Duddon]] estuary and surrounding countryside have made the area well known for its wildlife,<ref name=estuary/> while the villages' exposed position on the eastern bank facing the [[Irish Sea]] have encouraged the establishment of [[wind power|wind energy]] generation, amid local controversy.\n\n==History==\n\n===Ireleth===\n[[Image:Old Ireleth map (1850-1873).PNG|thumb|right|A map from between 1850 and 1873, showing Ireleth]]\n\nIreleth is the smaller and older of the two villages, with its origins stretching back to the [[Viking]] occupation of Britain. It was originally clustered along a stream, named 'Hole Beck', about half a mile up the hill from the estuary below. It was also the junction of four roads passing through the area. Firstly, there was the 'Sands' road, named 'Marsh Lane' in maps of the 1850s, heading down the hill towards the shore, where it met one of the possible routes for crossing the treacherous tidal sands of the [[River Duddon|Duddon]] at low tide. Secondly, there was the lane heading north along a ridge towards [[Kirkby-in-Furness]]. Part of these two roads form today's A595 main road. There was also a road leading up the stream's valley towards the hamlet of [[Marton, Cumbria|Marton]], and finally a road east over the hills towards [[Dalton-in-Furness]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planaccess.barrowbc.gov.uk/historicbarrow/PlanAccessGUI.html|title=Map from between 1850 and 1873, showing Ireleth|accessdate=24 March 2007|format=Flash|work=PlanAccess GUI|publisher=Barrow Borough Council|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030744/http://planaccess.barrowbc.gov.uk/historicbarrow/PlanAccessGUI.html|archivedate=28 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Viking]] origins exist in two forms: remains have been found near St. Peter's parish church<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> and the name of the village itself is Viking, translated from the [[Old Norse]] as 'hill-slope of the Irish'.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mills|first=David|title=The Place Names of Lancashire|year=1976|publisher=Batsford|location=London|isbn=0-7134-3248-9|page=100}}</ref>\n\nIt is thought the village was included in the [[Domesday Book]], compiled soon after the [[Norman Conquest]], but there is debate over which of the entries for the [[Furness]] area in [[William the Conqueror]]'s census actually refers to modern day Ireleth.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> Several sources name a settlement called ''Gerleuuorde'', part of the [[Manor of Hougun]], as the correct entry but there is no conclusive evidence to support this, not least because of the discrepancies in spelling.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> Samuel Lewis' ''A Topological Dictionary of England'', written 1848, posits a different contender as the true Ireleth. He claimed ''Ouregrave'' referred to the village because of the existence of a mill named ''Orga-Mill'', but he conceded this was also conjecture. Lewis' full text on Ireleth is below.<ref name= Topological>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Samuel|authorlink=Samuel Lewis (publisher)|title=A Topographical Dictionary of England|year=1848|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/source.asp?pubid=445|edition=Seventh|series=A Topographical Dictionary of...|publisher=Samuel Lewis and Co.|location=London, England|chapter=Ireleth|chapterurl=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=51064#s7}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\nIRELETH, a chapelry, in the parish of Dalton-In-Furness, union of Ulverston, hundred of Lonsdale north of the Sands, N. division of Lancashire, 3 miles (N.) from Dalton; containing 744 inhabitants. Ogra-Mill, in this township, has been conjectured to be the Ouregrave of the Domesday survey: Roanhead is the point for crossing Dudden sands by the ancient road into Cumberland. Upon the east borders of Ireleth, also called Above Town, are the iron-mines of Whitridge, Lindal Moor, Cross Gates, and Inman Gill, the richest and most productive mines in Furness, with the exception of Cross Gates, the works of which have been suspended. Many thousand tons of ore are raised annually in the township. The living is a perpetual curacy; net income, \u00a3100; patron, the Vicar of Dalton. The chapel was built in 1608, by Giles Brownrigg, and was originally intended for a school.\n}}\n\n[[Image:Irelethstpeters-improved.jpg|thumb|St. Peter's church (CoE), at the top of Ireleth]]\n\nDuring the [[Middle Ages]], the entire area was controlled by the [[Cistercian]] monks of [[Furness Abbey]]. During this time, Ireleth was little more than one of many farming communities in Furness. The iron ore developments of Askam largely bypassed Ireleth, and the village developed slowly, housing farmers and workers from local towns.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> The religious history of the village is recorded as starting around the year 1608, when an endowment was created to fund a village school. Giles Brownrigg, named variously as a local landowner<ref name=\"school history\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/history.htm |title=History of St Peter's Ireleth |accessdate=9 March 2007 |publisher=Ireleth St. Peter's school |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060926082257/http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/history.htm |archivedate=26 September 2006 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> or a tailor who had left the area to make his fortune in London,<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> gave money to establish a school house and a salary for a schoolmaster. This building existed on what is today Sun Street; the only remains today are a font and a plaque, kept in the modern day school building, inscribed:<ref name=\"school history\"/>\n\n{{cquote|\n''Giles Brownrig caused this school house to be builded the 6 yeare of King James ano 1608 and gave a yearly salari to the schole maister for ever [sic]''\n}}\n\nIreleth featured in the ''[[Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales]]''. In this, it is said-<ref name=\"Ireleth Imperial\">{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=John Marius|title=Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales|year=1872|chapter=Ireleth|chapterurl=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/descriptions/entry_page.jsp?text_id=752290&word=NULL}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\nIRELETH, a village and a chapelry in Dalton-in-Furness parish, Lancashire. The village stands at a st. of the Furness railway, on the E side of the Duddon sands, 2\u00be miles N of Dalton; is a small sub port to Lancaster; and maintains communication across the sands at low water. The chapelry includes also the hamlets of Lindale and Marton; but does not appear to have definite limits. Post town, Dalton-in-Furness. The living is a p. curacy in the diocese of Carlisle. Value, \u00a3100.* Patron, the Vicar of Dalton. The church stands on an eminence, overlooking the Duddon.\n}}\n\nIreleth did not have a parish church at this point, falling into the 'Above Town' area, together with the hamlets of Marton and Lindal, of the parish of [[Dalton-in-Furness]].<ref name=Topological/> Lacking a place of worship, it was decided the newly built school could also be put to use as a chapel. Fishwick's 'Lancashire & Cheshire Church Surveys, 1649\u20131655' of 1849 cites this record from a church survey taken in 1650:<ref>{{cite book|last=Fishwick|first=H.|title=Lancashire & Cheshire Church Surveys, 1649\u20131655|year=1879|chapter-format=Flash|pages=138|chapter=Parochial chapel: Dalton in Furness, Ireleth chapel|chapterurl= http://eagle.cch.kcl.ac.uk:8080/cce/locations/CreateLocationFrames.jsp?locKey=8869}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\nThat the Chappell of Irleth is not farr distant from its parish Church [Dalton in Furness], but neare enough thereto, and was onely built for a schoole, and some for their perticuler ease would have the same made a Chappell [sic]\n}}\n\nIn 1860, Ireleth, along with the newly founded Askam, petitioned for the creation of its own parish<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> following the rapid increase in population. Construction of a parish church began, with the money to build St. Peter's coming from the new-found profits of iron ore mining, giving rise to the name the 'Iron Church'. It was dedicated for use on St. Peter's Day, 29 June 1865,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.visitcumbria.com/sl/ireleth-and-askam-st-peters-church/|title=Ireleth & Askam \u2013 St Peter's Church|accessdate=1 April 2016|date=21 January 2005|publisher=Visit Cumbria}}</ref> but approval for a new ecclesiastical parish of 'Ireleth-with-Askam' did not come until almost ten years later in 1874.<ref>{{cite book|last=Youngs|first=F.|title=Local Administrative Units: Northern England|year=1991|publisher=Royal Historical Society|location=London, England|pages=176|chapter=Cited by A Vision of Britain Through Time, on their Askam With Ireleth entry|chapterurl=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10368583&c_id=}}</ref>\n\n===Askam===\n[[File:Askam Pier - south.jpg|thumb|right|The south side of the pier]]\n\nAskam's history starts much more recently. In 1850, iron ore deposits were discovered in the area by [[Henry Schneider]]. These turned out to be the second largest iron ore deposits in the country, with over 7 million tons of ore extracted. By 1896, 547 men were employed in the pits by the village and in nearby [[Roanhead]], 347 of them underground. Several hundred others worked in local mines at Mouzell (between Ireleth and [[Dalton-in-Furness]]), Roanhead and Dalton.<ref>{{cite book|year=1896|url=http://www.projects.ex.ac.uk/mhn/1896-35.htm|last=Hedley|first=John L.|title=Lancashire's Mining Industry in 1896 \u2013 A List of Metalliferous Mines|publisher=Britain's Active Mining History Society}}</ref> Some were owned by the [[Myles Burton Kennedy|Kennedy]] Brothers Ltd. firm of [[Ulverston]] Barrow Haematite Steel Co and the Millom and Askam Iron Company. The latter built four [[blast furnace]]s in the village to smelt the iron ore being brought from mines all over the peninsula by rail.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.banklands.com/Wagon%20labels.htm|title=A gallery of West Cumbrian railway wagon destination cards|accessdate=10 March 2007|last=Baggerly|first=Phil|publisher=banklands.com, a tribute to the Workington iron and steel industry}}</ref> The village continued to grow with terraced houses and allotments erected for the flood of immigrant labour needed to work the mines.<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\">{{cite web |accessdate=10 March 2007 |url=http://www.thecumbriadirectory.com/Town_or_Village/Askam_in_Furness/Askam_in_Furness.php |title=Askam in Furness Cumbria |publisher=The Cumbria Directory |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061120001255/http://www.thecumbriadirectory.com/Town_or_Village/Askam_in_Furness/Askam_in_Furness.php |archivedate=20 November 2006 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> They came from all parts of the [[British Isles]], with a large proportion coming from existing mining areas in [[Cornwall]] and Ireland. The Cornish in particular tended to bring their families and settle, while the Irish often moved on to wherever there was work. Others came from areas where Askam's mine owners had other concerns, such as Scotland and [[Wales]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.furnessfhs.co.uk/movement.htm|title=Migration and Movement|accessdate=10 March 2007|publisher=Furness Family History Society}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Askam and Ireleth signs.jpg|thumb|upright|An old Ireleth sign with a modern combined sign]]\n\nRemnants of the steel industry remain in Askam, as evidenced by a pier, consisting of slag from the works, that juts out into the bay toward [[Millom]].<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\"/> Also, numerous streets are named after the industry and its owners. For example, 'Steel Street' is so named because of the steel industry; 'Sharp Street' is named after Joseph Sharp, one of the earliest people involved in Askam's steel industry; and 'Crossley Street' after William Crossley, an early investor in the Askam steel industry.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> The large numbers of slag banks left by the steel industry around the village are now important sites for wildlife.<ref name=\"Estuary Booklet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/pdf/DuddonEstuary_Booklet.pdf |title=The Duddon Estuary |accessdate=10 March 2007 |last=Thomson |first=Rona |format=PDF |publisher=The Duddon Estuary Partnership |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208110018/http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/pdf/DuddonEstuary_Booklet.pdf |archivedate=8 February 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy }}</ref> By 1918, the iron ore had run out and most of the industrial buildings were demolished in 1933.<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\"/> Since then, Askam has grown with commuter homes, exploiting the views over the Duddon Estuary to the [[Lake District]].\n\n===Askam and Ireleth===\n\nAskam and Ireleth are both part of the Furness peninsula, where the suffix \"-in-Furness\" is sometimes added to place names, such as [[Barrow-in-Furness]] and [[Dalton-in-Furness]]. Askam, when referred to on its own, often uses this but it is rare for Ireleth to be called ''Ireleth-in-Furness''. \n\nHowever, Ireleth is often confused in archival records with 'Kirkby Ireleth', the former name for the community (two miles to the north) now known as [[Kirkby-in-Furness]]. These communities are differentiated in the ''Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales''.<ref name=\"Ireleth Imperial\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Samuel|authorlink=Samuel Lewis (publisher)|title=A Topographical Dictionary of England|year=1848 |edition=Seventh|series=A Topographical Dictionary of...|publisher=Samuel Lewis and Co.|location=London, England|chapter=Kirkby Ireleth|chapterurl=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=51082#s5}}</ref>\n\nWhile the strip development has effectively created one larger community in the past fifty years, residents of both villages still retain a strong sense of being either from Askam ''or'' Ireleth. Road signs read 'Askam and Ireleth' on entering the villages by road, but an older 'A595 \u2013 Ireleth' sign still stands on the former boundary between the two.\n\nIn administration terms, the civil parish of which they are both part uses the name Askam with Ireleth,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=362 |title=Parish and Town Councils |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=Barrow Borough Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310165732/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=362 |archivedate=10 March 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> as does the local [[Women's Institute|Women's Institute (WI)]] which had previously been called Ireleth WI.\n\n==Governance==\nAskam and Ireleth is part of the [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness parliamentary constituency]], represented by [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party ]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Simon Fell (politician)|Simon Fellk]]. \n\nFor [[Local Government]] purposes it is in the ''Dalton North [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|Ward]]'' of the [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Council]] and the ''Dalton North division'' of [[Cumbria County Council]].\n\nThe villages have their own [[Parish councils in England|parish council]]; ''Askam and Ireleth Parish Council.''<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 March 2007|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=362|title=Parish Councils|publisher=Barrow Borough Council|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070310165732/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=362|archivedate=10 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk/|title= Askam and Ireleth Parish Council}}</ref>\n\n==Environment==\nThe upper slopes of the hill near Ireleth are home to dark blue slate, and it is found on the roofs of several local dwellings. [[Haematite]], the bright red iron ore, was discovered in an exceptionally large deposit, the second largest in the country, south of the current villages in the 1840s. Askam sprung up on the Ireleth marshes as a home for the miners attacking the new deposit. The other mineral found in large quantities, conveniently with a commercial use, is [[shale]]. This is fired with water to make red brick, and the brickworks, which is still operational today, was built in 1845 to exploit this.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.lindal-in-furness.co.uk/Geology/geology1.htm|title=Geology of Furness & Cumbria|accessdate=10 March 2007|publisher=Lindal and Martin Community Website}}</ref>\n\nMuch wildlife is found on the Duddon Estuary, including 20% of the national [[natterjack toad]] population, who are attracted to the shallow breeding pools. The slagbanks around Askam are also very important as nesting sites for the rare [[Sandwich tern]]s that live in the area.<ref name=estuary>{{cite web |url=http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/wildlife.htm |title=Duddon Estuary Wildlife |accessdate=10 March 2007 |last=Hutchinson |first=Kate |publisher=Duddon Estuary Partnership |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070406202850/http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/wildlife.htm |archivedate=6 April 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> The beach is designated a [[SSSI|Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI)]] because of the range of flora and fauna present on the sands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.natureonthemap.org.uk/map.aspx?map=sssi&feature=1018367,sssi-su,HYPERLINK|title=Nature on the Map :: Maps|accessdate=10 March 2007|format=Flash|publisher=Natural England}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Askam and Ireleth Wind Farm]] can be found {{convert|1.25|mi|km|0}}  east of the village, on the southern slopes of Hare Slack Hill. Work on the turbines started in late 1998, and the wind farm took eight months to complete.\n\nThe [[Marton, Cumbria|Marton]], Askam and Ireleth Windfarm Action Group was one of the first such organisations in the UK dedicated to fighting windfarm development.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 March 2007 |url=http://www.windfarm.fsnet.co.uk/ |title=Living With Wind Turbines |year=2004 |publisher=MAIWAG |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060420072739/http://www.windfarm.fsnet.co.uk/ |archivedate=20 April 2006 |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Location and transport==\n[[File:Askam station, signalbox and crossing geograph-3240956-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|lrightAskam station and level crossing]]\n\nThe [[A595 road|A595]] is the main coastal route, designated a [[primary route]], connecting [[Dalton-in-Furness|Dalton]] and [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]] via the Cumbrian Coast. Its southern end is {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} south of Askam at the junction with the [[A590 road|A590]] Dalton-in-Furness bypass although formerly continued into Dalton. The area is served by the Blueworks X7 bus service on Wednesdays only.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/544/931/6586/6588/43406163930.pdf |title=Blueworks X7 Kirkby-In-Furness - Askam - Barrow |accessdate=14 November 2019 |format=PDF |publisher=Cumbria County Council}}</ref> There are plans to construct a crossing over the Duddon between Askam and [[Millom]] to reduce the long journey times between [[Furness]] and [[Copeland, Cumbria|Copeland]], due to the circuitous route of the A595 around the estuary. A scheme to build such a 'Duddon Crossing' remains at the planning stage, but is nominated as a future project in county transport planning.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 March 2007|date=November 2006|publisher=Cumbria County Council|format=PDF|url=http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/544/942/1503/3881911148.pdf|title=Area transport statements [page 24 of 50]|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010019/http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/544/942/1503/3881911148.pdf|archivedate=27 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe railway line passes through the two villages virtually bisecting them, with a bridge and a [[level crossing]] by the station allowing people to cross the line. There is a stop called [[Askam Railway Station]]. Services run south to Barrow and some continue on to the [[West Coast Mainline]] at [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]]. To the north the line links to the [[Sellafield|Sellafield nuclear power plant]], a major local employer, and onwards to [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]].\n\nAskam is located on the {{convert|150|mi|km|0}} [[Cumbrian Coastal Walk]], which winds around the edge of the county.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golakes.co.uk/Arnside-Cumbria-Coastal-Way/details/?dms=3&venue=5061122|title=Cumbria Coastal Way|accessdate=12 April 2016|publisher=GoLakes website, the official website of Cumbria Tourism}}</ref>\n\n{{NSEW|[[Kirkby-in-Furness]]|[[Barrow-in-Furness]]|[[Lindal-in-Furness]]|[[Duddon Estuary]]|[[Duddon Estuary]]|[[Marton, Cumbria|Marton]]|[[Duddon Estuary]]|[[Dalton-in-Furness]]}}\n\n==Sport==\nThe villages have several sporting facilities, including the Fallowfield Park rugby league ground, home of Askam Amateur [[Rugby league]] Football Club, known as the Sandrats. Formed on September 13, 1879,<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=10 March 2007 |url=http://www.sportskerlectables.com/enamelrugbybadges.htm |title=Eamel Rugby Badges (Askam ARLFC) |publisher=Sports Kerlectables |archivedate=10 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210032537/http://www.sportskerlectables.com/enamelrugbybadges.htm |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> the amateur club is a member of [[British Amateur Rugby League Association]] and in 2007\u20132008 were elected to the [[National Conference League]] Division 2, but withdrew before the start of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalconferenceleague.co.uk/ |title=Division Two Club Register |accessdate=10 March 2007 |format=Flash |publisher=National Conference League |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070303021954/http://www.nationalconferenceleague.co.uk/ |archivedate=3 March 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> There is Askam United [[association football|Football]] Club who play in the [[West Lancashire Football League]] Division Two and Duddon SC, a [[cricket]] team based at the old K Shoes factory social club, now called Duddon Sports and Social Club. There is also a newly formed junior football team and due to playing on the Sports Club pitches, has taken the name of Duddon Sports Junior Football Club.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=10 March 2007 |title=Clubs |url=http://barrowsportscouncil.org.uk/clubs.php |publisher=Barrow Sports Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070319052055/http://www.barrowsportscouncil.org.uk/clubs.php |archivedate=19 March 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA 10-hole [[links (golf)|links]] golf course, belonging to the Dunnerholme Golf Club, lies to the north of Askam. The course has one particularly interesting feature, namely a green atop Dunnerholme Rock,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-golfguide.com/england/25548.html |title=Dunnerholme Golf Club |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=UK Golf Guide |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211214812/http://www.uk-golfguide.com/england/25548.html |archivedate=11 February 2007 |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref> a large uneroded [[limestone]] rock which stands out from the surrounding flat course and sands.<ref name=\"Estuary Booklet\"/> The golf club has been in existence since 1905.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geocities.com/dunnerholmegolfclub |title=Dunnerholme Golf Club |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=Dunnerholme Golf Club |archivedate=6 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206004521/http://www.geocities.com/dunnerholmegolfclub |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Public buildings==\n\n===Village halls===\nAskam and Ireleth has four village halls: Temperance Hall in Ireleth, Askam Community Centre (formerly part of Askam School) which was refurbished in 2010, Band Hall in Sandy Lane, the home of Askam & Ireleth Silver Band, the local [[brass band]], and venue for dances, and Rankin Hall in Askam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk/links.html|title=Useful links and contacts|work=askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk|publisher=Askam and Ireleth Parish Council}}</ref> Temperance Hall was built by the [[Quakers]] in 1872;<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> it was marked as a place of worship on Ordnance Survey maps of the late 19th century, and was used by the [[Bible Christians]], a [[Methodism|Methodist]] denomination. It later fell out of use as a religious centre, being marked on maps in 1913 as simply a hall. The Temperance Hall was closed before being renovated in the 1990s, and is now used as a community centre and the location of [[Parish councils in England|parish council]] alternate months with the Rankin Hall, which is also the meeting place for the local [[Women's Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/SavesLaneBibleChristian.shtml|title=Saves Lane Bible Christian, Ireleth with Askam|accessdate=10 March 2007|last=Stringer|first=Phil|date=14 February 2007|publisher=GENUKI}}</ref>\n\n===Churchs===\nThere is St. Peter's Church overlooking the two villages atop Ireleth Hill, which is the oldest of the churches in the villages, and holds the only churchyard in the villages and adjoins the local cemetery; and the Temperance Hall that was once used as a church. There are three other places of worship within the village.\n\nIn 1907, at a cost of \u00a3350, The Christian Meeting House was built on Crossley Street in Askam, as a [[Church of Christ]] Church. This became, in 1956, [[Anthony the Great|St. Anthony]]'s [[Catholic]] Church, and is still used in that capacity today.  Sadly it is due to close by the end of 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/ChristianMeetingHouse.shtml|title= Christian Meeting House, Askam in Furness \u2013 Church of Christ|accessdate=11 March 2007|last=Stringer|first=Phil|date=14 February 2007|publisher=GENUKI}}</ref> On Duddon Road, in Askam, there is also a [[Methodism|Methodist]] Church, called Duddon Road Church.  This is a shared building with the Church of England and is the headquarters of the local scouts, cubs, beavers, rainbows and brownies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wakefield|first=Bill|publisher=BBC|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/faith/features/churches_of_cumbria/gallery/159.shtml|title=Cumbria's Places of Worship|accessdate=11 March 2007}} {{Dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere were once two other churches in the village, but they are no longer in use as Churches. Zion, on Beach Street, Askam, was a Primitive Methodist church that was founded in 1870. It closed in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/Zion.shtml|title=Zion, Ireleth with Askam \u2013 Primitive Methodist|accessdate=11 March 2007|last=Stringer|first=Phil|date=14 February 2007|publisher=GENUKI}}</ref> There was also a [[United Methodist]] Church in Askam, and though the building still stands on Duke Street, it is now used as a social club. The Church was opened in 1878, on land that was donated by the Furness Iron and Steel Company. and became the Rankin Hall (see above) The Gospel hall on Duke Street closed some five years ago.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/DukeStreetUnitedMethodistFreeChurch.shtml|title= Duke Street United Methodist Free Church, Ireleth with Askam|accessdate=11 March 2007 |last= Stringer|first= Phil|date= 14 February 2007|publisher= GENUKI}}</ref>\n\n===Schools===\nThere are two schools, Ireleth St Peter's [[Church of England]] Primary School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/ |title=St Peter's School |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=Ireleth St Peter's School |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070405081606/http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/ |archivedate=5 April 2007 |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref> and Askam Village School,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dfes.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/dfepx1_03.pl?Code=&No=909&Type=&Mode=&School=9095207|title=Askam Village School|accessdate=10 March 2007|year=2003|publisher=[[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department for Education and Skills]]|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040726185257/http://www.dfes.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/dfepx1_03.pl?Code=&No=909&Type=&Mode=&School=9095207|archivedate=26 July 2004|df=dmy-all}}</ref> both of which are primary schools. \n\n===Other buildings===\nThere is a [[Lifeboat (rescue)|lifeboat]] station, home of the Duddon Inshore Rescue, that was established in 1970.\n\nAskam has a fountain commemorating [[Queen Victoria]]'s [[Diamond Jubilee|Jubilee]].<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\"/> \n\nThere is a public library in Lord Street in Askam. It was originally built in 1904 as a reading room branch of Dalton-in-Furness Library.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Cumbria}}\n*[[Listed buildings in Askam and Ireleth]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Askam and Ireleth}}\n*[http://www.askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk/index.html Askam and Ireleth parish council]\n\n{{Barrow-in-Furness}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Askam And Ireleth}}\n[[Category:Furness]]\n[[Category:Districts of Barrow-in-Furness]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cumbria]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                England     \n|coordinates = {{coord|54.189|-3.204|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name=           Askam and Ireleth \n|civil_parish=            Askam and Ireleth\n|population =             3632\n|population_ref=          (2001)<ref name=\"Population\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/642/1752/1754/3837712243.xls|title=Cumbria population figures|accessdate=9 March 2007|year=2001|format=XLS|work=2001 census|publisher=Cumbria County Council|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010203/http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/536/642/1752/1754/3837712243.xls|archivedate=27 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|shire_district=          [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow-in-Furness]]\n|region=                  North West England\n|shire_county=            [[Cumbria]]\n|constituency_westminster=[[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness]]\n|post_town=               ASKAM-IN-FURNESS\n|postcode_district=       LA16\n|postcode_area=           LA \n|dial_code=               01229\n|os_grid_reference=       SD214777\n|static_image_name=       Askamandirelethlogo.jpg\n|static_image_alt=        Logo of the carish council on a rubbish bin.\n|static_image_caption=    The parish council logo. The roundel includes the initials of the villages on a symbolic representation of the beach, sea and fells.\n}}\n'''Askam and Ireleth''' is a [[civil parish]] close to [[Barrow-in-Furness]] in the county of Cumbria, in [[North West England]]. [[Historic counties of England|Historically]] part of [[Lancashire]], it originally consisted of two separate coastal villages with different origins and histories which, in recent times, have merged to become one continuous settlement. The population of the civil parish taken at the 2011 Census was 3,632.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11120167&c=Askam&d=16&e=62&g=6411250&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1453734226319&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIreleth has its origins as a [[mediaeval]] farming village clustered on the hillside overlooking the flat sands of the [[Duddon Estuary]].<ref name=\"A Short History\">{{cite web|accessdate=9 March 2007|publisher=Mark Maclean|url=http://users.hunterlink.net.au/~mbemdm/Ireleth_Askam_history.pdf|title=A Short History of Ireleth and Askam-in-Furness|last=Maclean|first=Mark|year=1997|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927025046/http://users.hunterlink.net.au/~mbemdm/Ireleth_Askam_history.pdf|archive-date=27 September 2007|url-status = dead}}</ref> Askam was established following the discovery of large quantities of iron ore near the village in the middle of the 18th century.\n\nThe pair originally fell within the boundaries of the [[Lonsdale (hundred)|Hundred of Lonsdale]] 'north of the sands' in the [[Historic counties of England|historic county]] of [[Lancashire]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043 |title=Lancashire AncC: Historical Boundaries |accessdate=9 March 2007 |publisher=A Vision of Britain Through Time |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001001412/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/bound_map_page.jsp?first=true&u_id=10173000&c_id=10001043 |archivedate=1 October 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy }}</ref> but following [[Local Government Act 1972|local government reforms]] in 1974 became part of the county of [[Cumbria]], along with the rest of [[Furness]].\n\nThe nearby [[River Duddon]] estuary and surrounding countryside have made the area well known for its wildlife,<ref name=estuary/> while the villages' exposed position on the eastern bank facing the [[Irish Sea]] have encouraged the establishment of [[wind power|wind energy]] generation, amid local controversy.\n\n==History==\n\n===Ireleth===\n[[Image:Old Ireleth map (1850-1873).PNG|thumb|right|A map from between 1850 and 1873, showing Ireleth]]\n\nIreleth is the smaller and older of the two villages, with its origins stretching back to the [[Viking]] occupation of Britain. It was originally clustered along a stream, named 'Hole Beck', about half a mile up the hill from the estuary below. It was also the junction of four roads passing through the area. Firstly, there was the 'Sands' road, named 'Marsh Lane' in maps of the 1850s, heading down the hill towards the shore, where it met one of the possible routes for crossing the treacherous tidal sands of the [[River Duddon|Duddon]] at low tide. Secondly, there was the lane heading north along a ridge towards [[Kirkby-in-Furness]]. Part of these two roads form today's A595 main road. There was also a road leading up the stream's valley towards the hamlet of [[Marton, Cumbria|Marton]], and finally a road east over the hills towards [[Dalton-in-Furness]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://planaccess.barrowbc.gov.uk/historicbarrow/PlanAccessGUI.html|title=Map from between 1850 and 1873, showing Ireleth|accessdate=24 March 2007|format=Flash|work=PlanAccess GUI|publisher=Barrow Borough Council|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928030744/http://planaccess.barrowbc.gov.uk/historicbarrow/PlanAccessGUI.html|archivedate=28 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Viking]] origins exist in two forms: remains have been found near St. Peter's parish church<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> and the name of the village itself is Viking, translated from the [[Old Norse]] as 'hill-slope of the Irish'.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mills|first=David|title=The Place Names of Lancashire|year=1976|publisher=Batsford|location=London|isbn=0-7134-3248-9|page=100}}</ref>\n\nIt is thought the village was included in the [[Domesday Book]], compiled soon after the [[Norman Conquest]], but there is debate over which of the entries for the [[Furness]] area in [[William the Conqueror]]'s census actually refers to modern day Ireleth.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> Several sources name a settlement called ''Gerleuuorde'', part of the [[Manor of Hougun]], as the correct entry but there is no conclusive evidence to support this, not least because of the discrepancies in spelling.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> Samuel Lewis' ''A Topological Dictionary of England'', written 1848, posits a different contender as the true Ireleth. He claimed ''Ouregrave'' referred to the village because of the existence of a mill named ''Orga-Mill'', but he conceded this was also conjecture. Lewis' full text on Ireleth is below.<ref name= Topological>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Samuel|authorlink=Samuel Lewis (publisher)|title=A Topographical Dictionary of England|year=1848|url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/source.asp?pubid=445|edition=Seventh|series=A Topographical Dictionary of...|publisher=Samuel Lewis and Co.|location=London, England|chapter=Ireleth|chapterurl=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=51064#s7}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\nIRELETH, a chapelry, in the parish of Dalton-In-Furness, union of Ulverston, hundred of Lonsdale north of the Sands, N. division of Lancashire, 3 miles (N.) from Dalton; containing 744 inhabitants. Ogra-Mill, in this township, has been conjectured to be the Ouregrave of the Domesday survey: Roanhead is the point for crossing Dudden sands by the ancient road into Cumberland. Upon the east borders of Ireleth, also called Above Town, are the iron-mines of Whitridge, Lindal Moor, Cross Gates, and Inman Gill, the richest and most productive mines in Furness, with the exception of Cross Gates, the works of which have been suspended. Many thousand tons of ore are raised annually in the township. The living is a perpetual curacy; net income, \u00a3100; patron, the Vicar of Dalton. The chapel was built in 1608, by Giles Brownrigg, and was originally intended for a school.\n}}\n\n[[Image:Irelethstpeters-improved.jpg|thumb|St. Peter's church (CoE), at the top of Ireleth]]\n\nDuring the [[Middle Ages]], the entire area was controlled by the [[Cistercian]] monks of [[Furness Abbey]]. During this time, Ireleth was little more than one of many farming communities in Furness. The iron ore developments of Askam largely bypassed Ireleth, and the village developed slowly, housing farmers and workers from local towns.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> The religious history of the village is recorded as starting around the year 1608, when an endowment was created to fund a village school. Giles Brownrigg, named variously as a local landowner<ref name=\"school history\">{{cite web |url=http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/history.htm |title=History of St Peter's Ireleth |accessdate=9 March 2007 |publisher=Ireleth St. Peter's school |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060926082257/http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/history.htm |archivedate=26 September 2006 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> or a tailor who had left the area to make his fortune in London,<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> gave money to establish a school house and a salary for a schoolmaster. This building existed on what is today Sun Street; the only remains today are a font and a plaque, kept in the modern day school building, inscribed:<ref name=\"school history\"/>\n\n{{cquote|\n''Giles Brownrig caused this school house to be builded the 6 yeare of King James ano 1608 and gave a yearly salari to the schole maister for ever [sic]''\n}}\n\nIreleth featured in the ''[[Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales]]''. In this, it is said-<ref name=\"Ireleth Imperial\">{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=John Marius|title=Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales|year=1872|chapter=Ireleth|chapterurl=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/descriptions/entry_page.jsp?text_id=752290&word=NULL}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\nIRELETH, a village and a chapelry in Dalton-in-Furness parish, Lancashire. The village stands at a st. of the Furness railway, on the E side of the Duddon sands, 2\u00be miles N of Dalton; is a small sub port to Lancaster; and maintains communication across the sands at low water. The chapelry includes also the hamlets of Lindale and Marton; but does not appear to have definite limits. Post town, Dalton-in-Furness. The living is a p. curacy in the diocese of Carlisle. Value, \u00a3100.* Patron, the Vicar of Dalton. The church stands on an eminence, overlooking the Duddon.\n}}\n\nIreleth did not have a parish church at this point, falling into the 'Above Town' area, together with the hamlets of Marton and Lindal, of the parish of [[Dalton-in-Furness]].<ref name=Topological/> Lacking a place of worship, it was decided the newly built school could also be put to use as a chapel. Fishwick's 'Lancashire & Cheshire Church Surveys, 1649\u20131655' of 1849 cites this record from a church survey taken in 1650:<ref>{{cite book|last=Fishwick|first=H.|title=Lancashire & Cheshire Church Surveys, 1649\u20131655|year=1879|chapter-format=Flash|pages=138|chapter=Parochial chapel: Dalton in Furness, Ireleth chapel|chapterurl= http://eagle.cch.kcl.ac.uk:8080/cce/locations/CreateLocationFrames.jsp?locKey=8869}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|\nThat the Chappell of Irleth is not farr distant from its parish Church [Dalton in Furness], but neare enough thereto, and was onely built for a schoole, and some for their perticuler ease would have the same made a Chappell [sic]\n}}\n\nIn 1860, Ireleth, along with the newly founded Askam, petitioned for the creation of its own parish<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> following the rapid increase in population. Construction of a parish church began, with the money to build St. Peter's coming from the new-found profits of iron ore mining, giving rise to the name the 'Iron Church'. It was dedicated for use on St. Peter's Day, 29 June 1865,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.visitcumbria.com/sl/ireleth-and-askam-st-peters-church/|title=Ireleth & Askam \u2013 St Peter's Church|accessdate=1 April 2016|date=21 January 2005|publisher=Visit Cumbria}}</ref> but approval for a new ecclesiastical parish of 'Ireleth-with-Askam' did not come until almost ten years later in 1874.<ref>{{cite book|last=Youngs|first=F.|title=Local Administrative Units: Northern England|year=1991|publisher=Royal Historical Society|location=London, England|pages=176|chapter=Cited by A Vision of Britain Through Time, on their Askam With Ireleth entry|chapterurl=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/relationships.jsp?u_id=10368583&c_id=}}</ref>\n\n===Askam===\n[[File:Askam Pier - south.jpg|thumb|right|The south side of the pier]]\n\nAskam's history starts much more recently. In 1850, iron ore deposits were discovered in the area by [[Henry Schneider]]. These turned out to be the second largest iron ore deposits in the country, with over 7 million tons of ore extracted. By 1896, 547 men were employed in the pits by the village and in nearby [[Roanhead]], 347 of them underground. Several hundred others worked in local mines at Mouzell (between Ireleth and [[Dalton-in-Furness]]), Roanhead and Dalton.<ref>{{cite book|year=1896|url=http://www.projects.ex.ac.uk/mhn/1896-35.htm|last=Hedley|first=John L.|title=Lancashire's Mining Industry in 1896 \u2013 A List of Metalliferous Mines|publisher=Britain's Active Mining History Society}}</ref> Some were owned by the [[Myles Burton Kennedy|Kennedy]] Brothers Ltd. firm of [[Ulverston]] Barrow Haematite Steel Co and the Millom and Askam Iron Company. The latter built four [[blast furnace]]s in the village to smelt the iron ore being brought from mines all over the peninsula by rail.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.banklands.com/Wagon%20labels.htm|title=A gallery of West Cumbrian railway wagon destination cards|accessdate=10 March 2007|last=Baggerly|first=Phil|publisher=banklands.com, a tribute to the Workington iron and steel industry}}</ref> The village continued to grow with terraced houses and allotments erected for the flood of immigrant labour needed to work the mines.<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\">{{cite web |accessdate=10 March 2007 |url=http://www.thecumbriadirectory.com/Town_or_Village/Askam_in_Furness/Askam_in_Furness.php |title=Askam in Furness Cumbria |publisher=The Cumbria Directory |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061120001255/http://www.thecumbriadirectory.com/Town_or_Village/Askam_in_Furness/Askam_in_Furness.php |archivedate=20 November 2006 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> They came from all parts of the [[British Isles]], with a large proportion coming from existing mining areas in [[Cornwall]] and Ireland. The Cornish in particular tended to bring their families and settle, while the Irish often moved on to wherever there was work. Others came from areas where Askam's mine owners had other concerns, such as Scotland and [[Wales]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.furnessfhs.co.uk/movement.htm|title=Migration and Movement|accessdate=10 March 2007|publisher=Furness Family History Society}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Askam and Ireleth signs.jpg|thumb|upright|An old Ireleth sign with a modern combined sign]]\n\nRemnants of the steel industry remain in Askam, as evidenced by a pier, consisting of slag from the works, that juts out into the bay toward [[Millom]].<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\"/> Also, numerous streets are named after the industry and its owners. For example, 'Steel Street' is so named because of the steel industry; 'Sharp Street' is named after Joseph Sharp, one of the earliest people involved in Askam's steel industry; and 'Crossley Street' after William Crossley, an early investor in the Askam steel industry.<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> The large numbers of slag banks left by the steel industry around the village are now important sites for wildlife.<ref name=\"Estuary Booklet\">{{cite web|url=http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/pdf/DuddonEstuary_Booklet.pdf |title=The Duddon Estuary |accessdate=10 March 2007 |last=Thomson |first=Rona |format=PDF |publisher=The Duddon Estuary Partnership |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208110018/http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/pdf/DuddonEstuary_Booklet.pdf |archivedate=8 February 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy }}</ref> By 1918, the iron ore had run out and most of the industrial buildings were demolished in 1933.<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\"/> Since then, Askam has grown with commuter homes, exploiting the views over the Duddon Estuary to the [[Lake District]].\n\n===Askam and Ireleth===\n\nAskam and Ireleth are both part of the Furness peninsula, where the suffix \"-in-Furness\" is sometimes added to place names, such as [[Barrow-in-Furness]] and [[Dalton-in-Furness]]. Askam, when referred to on its own, often uses this but it is rare for Ireleth to be called ''Ireleth-in-Furness''. \n\nHowever, Ireleth is often confused in archival records with 'Kirkby Ireleth', the former name for the community (two miles to the north) now known as [[Kirkby-in-Furness]]. These communities are differentiated in the ''Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales''.<ref name=\"Ireleth Imperial\"/><ref>{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Samuel|authorlink=Samuel Lewis (publisher)|title=A Topographical Dictionary of England|year=1848 |edition=Seventh|series=A Topographical Dictionary of...|publisher=Samuel Lewis and Co.|location=London, England|chapter=Kirkby Ireleth|chapterurl=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.asp?compid=51082#s5}}</ref>\n\nWhile the strip development has effectively created one larger community in the past fifty years, residents of both villages still retain a strong sense of being either from Askam ''or'' Ireleth. Road signs read 'Askam and Ireleth' on entering the villages by road, but an older 'A595 \u2013 Ireleth' sign still stands on the former boundary between the two.\n\nIn administration terms, the civil parish of which they are both part uses the name Askam with Ireleth,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/default.aspx?page=362 |title=Parish and Town Councils |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=Barrow Borough Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070310165732/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=362 |archivedate=10 March 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> as does the local [[Women's Institute|Women's Institute (WI)]] which had previously been called Ireleth WI.\n\n==Governance==\nAskam and Ireleth is part of the [[Barrow and Furness (UK Parliament constituency)|Barrow and Furness parliamentary constituency]], represented by [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party ]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] [[Simon Fell (politician)|Simon Fellk]]. \n\nFor [[Local Government]] purposes it is in the ''Dalton North [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|Ward]]'' of the [[Borough of Barrow-in-Furness|Barrow Council]] and the ''Dalton North division'' of [[Cumbria County Council]].\n\nThe villages have their own [[parish council]]; ''Askam and Ireleth Parish Council.''<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 March 2007|url= http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=362|title=Parish Councils|publisher=Barrow Borough Council|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070310165732/http://www.barrowbc.gov.uk/Default.aspx?page=362|archivedate=10 March 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk/|title= Askam and Ireleth Parish Council}}</ref>\n\n==Environment==\nThe upper slopes of the hill near Ireleth are home to dark blue slate, and it is found on the roofs of several local dwellings. [[Haematite]], the bright red iron ore, was discovered in an exceptionally large deposit, the second largest in the country, south of the current villages in the 1840s. Askam sprung up on the Ireleth marshes as a home for the miners attacking the new deposit. The other mineral found in large quantities, conveniently with a commercial use, is [[shale]]. This is fired with water to make red brick, and the brickworks, which is still operational today, was built in 1845 to exploit this.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.lindal-in-furness.co.uk/Geology/geology1.htm|title=Geology of Furness & Cumbria|accessdate=10 March 2007|publisher=Lindal and Martin Community Website}}</ref>\n\nMuch wildlife is found on the Duddon Estuary, including 20% of the national [[natterjack toad]] population, who are attracted to the shallow breeding pools. The slagbanks around Askam are also very important as nesting sites for the rare [[Sandwich tern]]s that live in the area.<ref name=estuary>{{cite web |url=http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/wildlife.htm |title=Duddon Estuary Wildlife |accessdate=10 March 2007 |last=Hutchinson |first=Kate |publisher=Duddon Estuary Partnership |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070406202850/http://www.duddon-estuary.org.uk/wildlife.htm |archivedate=6 April 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> The beach is designated a [[SSSI|Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI)]] because of the range of flora and fauna present on the sands.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.natureonthemap.org.uk/map.aspx?map=sssi&feature=1018367,sssi-su,HYPERLINK|title=Nature on the Map :: Maps|accessdate=10 March 2007|format=Flash|publisher=Natural England}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Askam and Ireleth Wind Farm]] can be found {{convert|1.25|mi|km|0}}  east of the village, on the southern slopes of Hare Slack Hill. Work on the turbines started in late 1998, and the wind farm took eight months to complete.\n\nThe [[Marton, Cumbria|Marton]], Askam and Ireleth Windfarm Action Group was one of the first such organisations in the UK dedicated to fighting windfarm development.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 March 2007 |url=http://www.windfarm.fsnet.co.uk/ |title=Living With Wind Turbines |year=2004 |publisher=MAIWAG |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060420072739/http://www.windfarm.fsnet.co.uk/ |archivedate=20 April 2006 |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Location and transport==\n[[File:Askam station, signalbox and crossing geograph-3240956-by-Ben-Brooksbank.jpg|thumb|lrightAskam station and level crossing]]\n\nThe [[A595 road|A595]] is the main coastal route, designated a [[primary route]], connecting [[Dalton-in-Furness|Dalton]] and [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]] via the Cumbrian Coast. Its southern end is {{convert|2|mi|km|0}} south of Askam at the junction with the [[A590 road|A590]] Dalton-in-Furness bypass although formerly continued into Dalton. The area is served by the Blueworks X7 bus service on Wednesdays only.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/544/931/6586/6588/43406163930.pdf |title=Blueworks X7 Kirkby-In-Furness - Askam - Barrow |accessdate=14 November 2019 |format=PDF |publisher=Cumbria County Council}}</ref> There are plans to construct a crossing over the Duddon between Askam and [[Millom]] to reduce the long journey times between [[Furness]] and [[Copeland, Cumbria|Copeland]], due to the circuitous route of the A595 around the estuary. A scheme to build such a 'Duddon Crossing' remains at the planning stage, but is nominated as a future project in county transport planning.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 March 2007|date=November 2006|publisher=Cumbria County Council|format=PDF|url=http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/544/942/1503/3881911148.pdf|title=Area transport statements [page 24 of 50]|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927010019/http://www.cumbria.gov.uk/elibrary/Content/Internet/544/942/1503/3881911148.pdf|archivedate=27 September 2007|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe railway line passes through the two villages virtually bisecting them, with a bridge and a [[level crossing]] by the station allowing people to cross the line. There is a stop called [[Askam Railway Station]]. Services run south to Barrow and some continue on to the [[West Coast Mainline]] at [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]]. To the north the line links to the [[Sellafield|Sellafield nuclear power plant]], a major local employer, and onwards to [[Carlisle, Cumbria|Carlisle]].\n\nAskam is located on the {{convert|150|mi|km|0}} [[Cumbrian Coastal Walk]], which winds around the edge of the county.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.golakes.co.uk/Arnside-Cumbria-Coastal-Way/details/?dms=3&venue=5061122|title=Cumbria Coastal Way|accessdate=12 April 2016|publisher=GoLakes website, the official website of Cumbria Tourism}}</ref>\n\n{{NSEW|[[Kirkby-in-Furness]]|[[Barrow-in-Furness]]|[[Lindal-in-Furness]]|[[Duddon Estuary]]|[[Duddon Estuary]]|[[Marton, Cumbria|Marton]]|[[Duddon Estuary]]|[[Dalton-in-Furness]]}}\n\n==Sport==\nThe villages have several sporting facilities, including the Fallowfield Park rugby league ground, home of Askam Amateur [[Rugby league]] Football Club, known as the Sandrats. Formed on September 13, 1879,<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=10 March 2007 |url=http://www.sportskerlectables.com/enamelrugbybadges.htm |title=Eamel Rugby Badges (Askam ARLFC) |publisher=Sports Kerlectables |archivedate=10 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070210032537/http://www.sportskerlectables.com/enamelrugbybadges.htm |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> the amateur club is a member of [[British Amateur Rugby League Association]] and in 2007\u20132008 were elected to the [[National Conference League]] Division 2, but withdrew before the start of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalconferenceleague.co.uk/ |title=Division Two Club Register |accessdate=10 March 2007 |format=Flash |publisher=National Conference League |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070303021954/http://www.nationalconferenceleague.co.uk/ |archivedate=3 March 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> There is Askam United [[association football|Football]] Club who play in the [[West Lancashire Football League]] Division Two and Duddon SC, a [[cricket]] team based at the old K Shoes factory social club, now called Duddon Sports and Social Club. There is also a newly formed junior football team and due to playing on the Sports Club pitches, has taken the name of Duddon Sports Junior Football Club.<ref>{{cite web |accessdate=10 March 2007 |title=Clubs |url=http://barrowsportscouncil.org.uk/clubs.php |publisher=Barrow Sports Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070319052055/http://www.barrowsportscouncil.org.uk/clubs.php |archivedate=19 March 2007 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nA 10-hole [[links (golf)|links]] golf course, belonging to the Dunnerholme Golf Club, lies to the north of Askam. The course has one particularly interesting feature, namely a green atop Dunnerholme Rock,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uk-golfguide.com/england/25548.html |title=Dunnerholme Golf Club |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=UK Golf Guide |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070211214812/http://www.uk-golfguide.com/england/25548.html |archivedate=11 February 2007 |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref> a large uneroded [[limestone]] rock which stands out from the surrounding flat course and sands.<ref name=\"Estuary Booklet\"/> The golf club has been in existence since 1905.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geocities.com/dunnerholmegolfclub |title=Dunnerholme Golf Club |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=Dunnerholme Golf Club |archivedate=6 February 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070206004521/http://www.geocities.com/dunnerholmegolfclub |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==Public buildings==\n\n===Village halls===\nAskam and Ireleth has four village halls: Temperance Hall in Ireleth, Askam Community Centre (formerly part of Askam School) which was refurbished in 2010, Band Hall in Sandy Lane, the home of Askam & Ireleth Silver Band, the local [[brass band]], and venue for dances, and Rankin Hall in Askam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk/links.html|title=Useful links and contacts|work=askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk|publisher=Askam and Ireleth Parish Council}}</ref> Temperance Hall was built by the [[Quakers]] in 1872;<ref name=\"A Short History\"/> it was marked as a place of worship on Ordnance Survey maps of the late 19th century, and was used by the [[Bible Christians]], a [[Methodism|Methodist]] denomination. It later fell out of use as a religious centre, being marked on maps in 1913 as simply a hall. The Temperance Hall was closed before being renovated in the 1990s, and is now used as a community centre and the location of [[Parish councils in England|parish council]] alternate months with the Rankin Hall, which is also the meeting place for the local [[Women's Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/SavesLaneBibleChristian.shtml|title=Saves Lane Bible Christian, Ireleth with Askam|accessdate=10 March 2007|last=Stringer|first=Phil|date=14 February 2007|publisher=GENUKI}}</ref>\n\n===Churchs===\nThere is St. Peter's Church overlooking the two villages atop Ireleth Hill, which is the oldest of the churches in the villages, and holds the only churchyard in the villages and adjoins the local cemetery; and the Temperance Hall that was once used as a church. There are three other places of worship within the village.\n\nIn 1907, at a cost of \u00a3350, The Christian Meeting House was built on Crossley Street in Askam, as a [[Church of Christ]] Church. This became, in 1956, [[Anthony the Great|St. Anthony]]'s [[Catholic]] Church, and is still used in that capacity today.  Sadly it is due to close by the end of 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/ChristianMeetingHouse.shtml|title= Christian Meeting House, Askam in Furness \u2013 Church of Christ|accessdate=11 March 2007|last=Stringer|first=Phil|date=14 February 2007|publisher=GENUKI}}</ref> On Duddon Road, in Askam, there is also a [[Methodism|Methodist]] Church, called Duddon Road Church.  This is a shared building with the Church of England and is the headquarters of the local scouts, cubs, beavers, rainbows and brownies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wakefield|first=Bill|publisher=BBC|url= http://www.bbc.co.uk/cumbria/faith/features/churches_of_cumbria/gallery/159.shtml|title=Cumbria's Places of Worship|accessdate=11 March 2007}} {{Dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere were once two other churches in the village, but they are no longer in use as Churches. Zion, on Beach Street, Askam, was a Primitive Methodist church that was founded in 1870. It closed in 1985.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/Zion.shtml|title=Zion, Ireleth with Askam \u2013 Primitive Methodist|accessdate=11 March 2007|last=Stringer|first=Phil|date=14 February 2007|publisher=GENUKI}}</ref> There was also a [[United Methodist]] Church in Askam, and though the building still stands on Duke Street, it is now used as a social club. The Church was opened in 1878, on land that was donated by the Furness Iron and Steel Company. and became the Rankin Hall (see above) The Gospel hall on Duke Street closed some five years ago.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Ireleth/DukeStreetUnitedMethodistFreeChurch.shtml|title= Duke Street United Methodist Free Church, Ireleth with Askam|accessdate=11 March 2007 |last= Stringer|first= Phil|date= 14 February 2007|publisher= GENUKI}}</ref>\n\n===Schools===\nThere are two schools, Ireleth St Peter's [[Church of England]] Primary School<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/ |title=St Peter's School |accessdate=10 March 2007 |publisher=Ireleth St Peter's School |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070405081606/http://www.irelethst-peters.cumbria.sch.uk/ |archivedate=5 April 2007 |url-status = live|df=dmy }}</ref> and Askam Village School,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dfes.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/dfepx1_03.pl?Code=&No=909&Type=&Mode=&School=9095207|title=Askam Village School|accessdate=10 March 2007|year=2003|publisher=[[Department for Education and Skills (United Kingdom)|Department for Education and Skills]]|url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040726185257/http://www.dfes.gov.uk/cgi-bin/performancetables/dfepx1_03.pl?Code=&No=909&Type=&Mode=&School=9095207|archivedate=26 July 2004|df=dmy-all}}</ref> both of which are primary schools. \n\n===Other buildings===\nThere is a [[Lifeboat (rescue)|lifeboat]] station, home of the Duddon Inshore Rescue, that was established in 1970.\n\nAskam has a fountain commemorating [[Queen Victoria]]'s [[Diamond Jubilee|Jubilee]].<ref name=\"Cumbria Directory- Askam\"/> \n\nThere is a public library in Lord Street in Askam. It was originally built in 1904 as a reading room branch of Dalton-in-Furness Library.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Cumbria}}\n*[[Listed buildings in Askam and Ireleth]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Askam and Ireleth}}\n*[http://www.askamandirelethparishcouncil.org.uk/index.html Askam and Ireleth parish council]\n\n{{Barrow-in-Furness}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Askam And Ireleth}}\n[[Category:Furness]]\n[[Category:Districts of Barrow-in-Furness]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cumbria]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toParish council(link changed toParish councils in England) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Askam_and_Ireleth"}
{"title_page": "Shap", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\n|static_image_name             =  Shap - Market Cross.jpg\n|static_image_caption =  Shap Market Cross\n|coordinates   = {{coord|54.529|-2.676|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name      = Shap\n|population = 1,264\n|population_ref=  ''(2011)''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11128353&c=CA10+3LR&d=16&e=62&g=6412206&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=0&s=1434986401391&enc=1|title=Parish population 2011|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref>\n|civil_parish= Shap\n|shire_district= [[Eden, Cumbria|Eden]]\n|shire_county = [[Cumbria]]\n|region = North West England\n|constituency_westminster = [[Penrith and the Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and the Border]]\n|post_town = PENRITH\n|postcode_district = CA10\n|postcode_area =  CA\n|dial_code = 01931\n|os_grid_reference =  NY563150\n}}\n\n'''Shap''' is a [[linear village]] and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] located among [[fell]]s and isolated [[Valley|dales]] in [[Eden, Cumbria|Eden district]], [[Cumbria]],  in the [[Historic counties of England|historic county]] of [[Westmorland]]. \n\n==Location==\nThe village lies along the [[A6 road (Great Britain)|A6 road]] and the [[West Coast Main Line]], and is near to the [[M6 motorway]]. It is situated {{convert|10|mi|0}} from [[Penrith, Cumbria|Penrith]] and about {{convert|15|mi|0}} from [[Kendal]].\n\nShap is on the route of the [[Coast to Coast Walk]].\n\n==Etymology==\nEarly (12th and 13th century) forms such as ''Hep'' and ''Yheppe'' point to an [[Old Norse]] rendering ''Hj\u00e1p'' of an [[Old English language|Old English]] original ''H\u0113ap'' = \"heap\", (of stones), probably referring to an ancient [[stone circle]], [[cairn]], or to the [[Shap Stone Avenue]] just to the west of the village.<ref name=\"Whaley\">{{Cite book|last=Whaley|first=Diana|title=A dictionary of Lake District place-names|location=Nottingham|publisher=English Place-Name Society|year=2006|pages=lx,423 p.305|ISBN=0904889726}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAlthough Shap is geographically a small village, it is legally a [[market town]] with a charter dating from the 17th century. The parish was, between 1905 and 1935, administered by an [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]] council. At one time, the granite works (which are situated about a mile outside the village) was in itself a separate community, with its own [[Co-op UK|Co-op]].  Shap polished pink granite can be found in many buildings in the UK, including outside [[St Paul\u2019s Cathedral]] in London\n\n==Shap today==\n[[File:St Michaels Church, Shap with Swindale - geograph.org.uk - 551119.jpg|thumb|right|St. Michael's Church]]\nThe village has three [[pubs]], a small supermarket, a [[fish & chips|fish and chip]] shop, an antique book shop, a butcher's shop, a primary school, a newsagent's, a coffee shop, a ceramic art studio called ''Edge Ceramics'', a [[fire station]], a shoe shop ([[New Balance]] factory shop) an [[Anglican]] church and 3 B&B/ Hostels.  There is also a small library, this is in the process of being relinquished from local council control and being adopted by the community as part of a budget cutting measure.\n\nMajor employers in the area are [[Hanson plc|Hanson]] and [[Tata Steel]].\n\nSome of the scenes in the feature film ''[[Withnail and I]]'' were filmed around Shap. [[Sleddale Hall]], the filming location for Uncle Monty's cottage Crow Crag, is located near [[Sleddale Hall|Wet Sleddale Reservoir]].\n\nOn 22 October 1999, a [[BAE Hawk|Hawk jet]] from [[RAF Leeming]] crashed into an empty barn in the village before disintegrating across the A6 and West Coast railway line, killing its two-man crew.\n\n==Attractions==\n[[File:Shap Summit - geograph.org.uk - 535853.jpg|thumb|right|Shap Summit]]\n'''Shap [[Route summit|Summit]]''' is located on the motorway at {{gbmappingsmall|NY583120}} and the railway at {{gbmappingsmall|NY570110}}.\nShap Fell used to be notorious for the difficult and dangerous stretch of A6 for drivers, and it includes a well-known section of the West Coast Main Line.  It has a 1:75 gradient for trains heading north, and in the days of steam locomotives banking engines from Tebay were often used to assist trains. It has been popular with railway photographers and there have been many pictures published taken in the area, most notably at [[Scout Green]] which lies on the southern approach to the hill.\n\n'''Shap Fell''' {{gbmappingsmall|NY530088}} is known for Shap [[granite]]<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.es.ucl.ac.uk/schools/Glossary/granite.htm |title = Shap granite}}</ref> that is a pink rock rich in [[orthoclase]], [[quartz]] and [[biotite]]; Shap Pink Quarry {{gbmappingsmall|NY557083}} takes its name from this.\n\n'''[[Shap Abbey]]''' {{gbmappingsmall|NY547151}} is nearby in the secluded valley of the river Lowther. Impressive ruins dating from 1199. The Abbey was one of the last to be dissolved by [[Henry VIII]] in 1540.\n\n'''Shap Wells''' has a [[mineral spa]] located in the grounds of the Shap Wells hotel which was used in [[World War II]] as a [[List of POW camps in Britain|prisoner of war camp]].\n\n==In literature==\n\nA scene in [[Robert Neill (writer)|Robert Neill]]'s historical novel ''Crown and Mitre'' is laid in Shap. In 1659 the book's protagonist Hal Burnaby, a young Royalist, rides through the village on a clandestine mission connected with the restoration of King Charles II.\nShap also appears in [[Anthony Trollope]]'s novel ''[[Can You Forgive Her?]]'' as the nearest village to Vavasor Hall, the ancestral home of the heroine Alice Vavasor.\n\n==Governance==\nThe [[civil parish]] of Shap (formerly Shap Urban Parish) includes the hamlet of [[Keld, Cumbria|Keld]] and parts of the granite works and limestone works, and has a population of 1,221,<ref>[http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790349 Office for National Statistics : ''Census 2001 : Parish Headcounts : Eden''] Retrieved 21 November 2009</ref> increasing to 1,264 at the 2011 Census.  The parish shares a joint parish council and an [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] with [[Shap Rural]]. The total population of the electoral ward taken at the 2011 census was 1,394.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/shap-e05003231#sthash.ZHAKRXxx.dpbs|title=Ward population 2011|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nShap is in the [[United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|parliamentary constituency]] of [[Penrith and The Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and the Border]]. [[Neil Hudson (politician)|Neil Hudson]] was elected its Conservative [[Member of Parliament]] at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 General Election]], replacing [[Rory Stewart]].\n\nPrior to [[Brexit]], for the [[European Parliament]] its residents voted to elect [[Members of the European Parliament|MEP]]'s for the [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West England]] constituency.\n\nFor [[Local Government]] purposes it is in the ''Shap Ward'' of [[Eden District|Eden District Council]] and the ''Eden Lakes Division'' of [[Cumbria County Council]].\n\nShap has its own [[Parish councils in England|parish council]]; ''Shap Parish Council''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://shapcumbria.wordpress.com/parish-council/|title= Shap Parish Council}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://councilportal.cumbria.gov.uk/mgParishCouncilDetails.aspx?ID=555&LS=1|title= councilportal.cumbria.gov.uk - Shap Parish Council}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nThe [[Lancaster and Carlisle Railway]] (now part of the [[West Coast Main Line]]), opened on 17 December 1846, and runs along the eastern edge of the village. [[Shap railway station]] was closed in 1968, though there have been calls for its re-opening.<ref>{{cite news |title=Plea to reopen Shap and Tebay rail stations |url=http://www.cwherald.com/a/archive/plea-to-reopen-shap-and-tebay-rail-stations.397646.html |accessdate=2018-06-22 |work=Cumberland & Westmorland Herald |date=2012-09-21}}</ref> [[Penrith railway station|Penrith]] is the closest railway station and is situated on the West Coast Main Line.\n\n== Dialect ==\nThe people of Shap speak a variant of the ''Penrithian'' dialect, which is itself a variant of the [[Cumbrian dialect]] spoken around the Penrith and Eden district area.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cumbria}}\n*[[Listed buildings in Shap]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Shap}}\n*[http://www.cumbriacountyhistory.org.uk/township/shap   Cumbria County History Trust: Shap] (nb: provisional research only \u2013 see Talk page)\n* [http://www.shapcumbria.co.uk Shap Community Website \u2013 Maintained by the Parish Council]\n* [http://www.gravestonepix.com/contents1a/2009/10/shap-air-crash-anniversary/ Shap Air Crash Anniversary]\n* [http://www.gravestonepix.com/contents1a/2009/10/rail-workers-monument-shap/ Rail Worker's Monument, Shap]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vfc4bBY8puE Video footage and history of Keld Chapel]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CK498sf-ujU Video footage of the Shap Wells Spa and Hotel]\n{{NSEW|[[Penrith, Cumbria|Penrith]]|[[Kendal]]|[[Maulds Meaburn]]|[[Haweswater Reservoir|Haweswater]]|||||}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Westmorland]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Eden District]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country = England\n|static_image_name             =  Shap - Market Cross.jpg\n|static_image_caption =  Shap Market Cross\n|coordinates   = {{coord|54.529|-2.676|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name      = Shap\n|population = 1,264\n|population_ref=  ''(2011)''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11128353&c=CA10+3LR&d=16&e=62&g=6412206&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=0&s=1434986401391&enc=1|title=Parish population 2011|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref>\n|civil_parish= Shap\n|shire_district= [[Eden, Cumbria|Eden]]\n|shire_county = [[Cumbria]]\n|region = North West England\n|constituency_westminster = [[Penrith and the Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and the Border]]\n|post_town = PENRITH\n|postcode_district = CA10\n|postcode_area =  CA\n|dial_code = 01931\n|os_grid_reference =  NY563150\n}}\n\n'''Shap''' is a [[linear village]] and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] located among [[fell]]s and isolated [[Valley|dales]] in [[Eden, Cumbria|Eden district]], [[Cumbria]],  in the [[Historic counties of England|historic county]] of [[Westmorland]]. \n\n==Location==\nThe village lies along the [[A6 road (Great Britain)|A6 road]] and the [[West Coast Main Line]], and is near to the [[M6 motorway]]. It is situated {{convert|10|mi|0}} from [[Penrith, Cumbria|Penrith]] and about {{convert|15|mi|0}} from [[Kendal]].\n\nShap is on the route of the [[Coast to Coast Walk]].\n\n==Etymology==\nEarly (12th and 13th century) forms such as ''Hep'' and ''Yheppe'' point to an [[Old Norse]] rendering ''Hj\u00e1p'' of an [[Old English language|Old English]] original ''H\u0113ap'' = \"heap\", (of stones), probably referring to an ancient [[stone circle]], [[cairn]], or to the [[Shap Stone Avenue]] just to the west of the village.<ref name=\"Whaley\">{{Cite book|last=Whaley|first=Diana|title=A dictionary of Lake District place-names|location=Nottingham|publisher=English Place-Name Society|year=2006|pages=lx,423 p.305|ISBN=0904889726}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nAlthough Shap is geographically a small village, it is legally a [[market town]] with a charter dating from the 17th century. The parish was, between 1905 and 1935, administered by an [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]] council. At one time, the granite works (which are situated about a mile outside the village) was in itself a separate community, with its own [[Co-op UK|Co-op]].  Shap polished pink granite can be found in many buildings in the UK, including outside [[St Paul\u2019s Cathedral]] in London\n\n==Shap today==\n[[File:St Michaels Church, Shap with Swindale - geograph.org.uk - 551119.jpg|thumb|right|St. Michael's Church]]\nThe village has three [[pubs]], a small supermarket, a [[fish & chips|fish and chip]] shop, an antique book shop, a butcher's shop, a primary school, a newsagent's, a coffee shop, a ceramic art studio called ''Edge Ceramics'', a [[fire station]], a shoe shop ([[New Balance]] factory shop) an [[Anglican]] church and 3 B&B/ Hostels.  There is also a small library, this is in the process of being relinquished from local council control and being adopted by the community as part of a budget cutting measure.\n\nMajor employers in the area are [[Hanson plc|Hanson]] and [[Tata Steel]].\n\nSome of the scenes in the feature film ''[[Withnail and I]]'' were filmed around Shap. [[Sleddale Hall]], the filming location for Uncle Monty's cottage Crow Crag, is located near [[Sleddale Hall|Wet Sleddale Reservoir]].\n\nOn 22 October 1999, a [[BAE Hawk|Hawk jet]] from [[RAF Leeming]] crashed into an empty barn in the village before disintegrating across the A6 and West Coast railway line, killing its two-man crew.\n\n==Attractions==\n[[File:Shap Summit - geograph.org.uk - 535853.jpg|thumb|right|Shap Summit]]\n'''Shap [[Route summit|Summit]]''' is located on the motorway at {{gbmappingsmall|NY583120}} and the railway at {{gbmappingsmall|NY570110}}.\nShap Fell used to be notorious for the difficult and dangerous stretch of A6 for drivers, and it includes a well-known section of the West Coast Main Line.  It has a 1:75 gradient for trains heading north, and in the days of steam locomotives banking engines from Tebay were often used to assist trains. It has been popular with railway photographers and there have been many pictures published taken in the area, most notably at [[Scout Green]] which lies on the southern approach to the hill.\n\n'''Shap Fell''' {{gbmappingsmall|NY530088}} is known for Shap [[granite]]<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.es.ucl.ac.uk/schools/Glossary/granite.htm |title = Shap granite}}</ref> that is a pink rock rich in [[orthoclase]], [[quartz]] and [[biotite]]; Shap Pink Quarry {{gbmappingsmall|NY557083}} takes its name from this.\n\n'''[[Shap Abbey]]''' {{gbmappingsmall|NY547151}} is nearby in the secluded valley of the river Lowther. Impressive ruins dating from 1199. The Abbey was one of the last to be dissolved by [[Henry VIII]] in 1540.\n\n'''Shap Wells''' has a [[mineral spa]] located in the grounds of the Shap Wells hotel which was used in [[World War II]] as a [[List of POW camps in Britain|prisoner of war camp]].\n\n==In literature==\n\nA scene in [[Robert Neill (writer)|Robert Neill]]'s historical novel ''Crown and Mitre'' is laid in Shap. In 1659 the book's protagonist Hal Burnaby, a young Royalist, rides through the village on a clandestine mission connected with the restoration of King Charles II.\nShap also appears in [[Anthony Trollope]]'s novel ''[[Can You Forgive Her?]]'' as the nearest village to Vavasor Hall, the ancestral home of the heroine Alice Vavasor.\n\n==Governance==\nThe [[civil parish]] of Shap (formerly Shap Urban Parish) includes the hamlet of [[Keld, Cumbria|Keld]] and parts of the granite works and limestone works, and has a population of 1,221,<ref>[http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/viewFullDataset.do?instanceSelection=03070&productId=779&$ph=60_61&datasetInstanceId=3070&startColumn=1&numberOfColumns=8&containerAreaId=790349 Office for National Statistics : ''Census 2001 : Parish Headcounts : Eden''] Retrieved 21 November 2009</ref> increasing to 1,264 at the 2011 Census.  The parish shares a joint parish council and an [[Wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] with [[Shap Rural]]. The total population of the electoral ward taken at the 2011 census was 1,394.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukcensusdata.com/shap-e05003231#sthash.ZHAKRXxx.dpbs|title=Ward population 2011|accessdate=22 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nShap is in the [[United Kingdom Parliament constituencies|parliamentary constituency]] of [[Penrith and The Border (UK Parliament constituency)|Penrith and the Border]]. [[Neil Hudson (politician)|Neil Hudson]] was elected its Conservative [[Member of Parliament]] at the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 General Election]], replacing [[Rory Stewart]].\n\nPrior to [[Brexit]], for the [[European Parliament]] its residents voted to elect [[Members of the European Parliament|MEP]]'s for the [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West England]] constituency.\n\nFor [[Local Government]] purposes it is in the ''Shap Ward'' of [[Eden District|Eden District Council]] and the ''Eden Lakes Division'' of [[Cumbria County Council]].\n\nShap has its own [[parish council]]; ''Shap Parish Council''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://shapcumbria.wordpress.com/parish-council/|title= Shap Parish Council}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://councilportal.cumbria.gov.uk/mgParishCouncilDetails.aspx?ID=555&LS=1|title= councilportal.cumbria.gov.uk - Shap Parish Council}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nThe [[Lancaster and Carlisle Railway]] (now part of the [[West Coast Main Line]]), opened on 17 December 1846, and runs along the eastern edge of the village. [[Shap railway station]] was closed in 1968, though there have been calls for its re-opening.<ref>{{cite news |title=Plea to reopen Shap and Tebay rail stations |url=http://www.cwherald.com/a/archive/plea-to-reopen-shap-and-tebay-rail-stations.397646.html |accessdate=2018-06-22 |work=Cumberland & Westmorland Herald |date=2012-09-21}}</ref> [[Penrith railway station|Penrith]] is the closest railway station and is situated on the West Coast Main Line.\n\n== Dialect ==\nThe people of Shap speak a variant of the ''Penrithian'' dialect, which is itself a variant of the [[Cumbrian dialect]] spoken around the Penrith and Eden district area.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cumbria}}\n*[[Listed buildings in Shap]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Shap}}\n*[http://www.cumbriacountyhistory.org.uk/township/shap   Cumbria County History Trust: Shap] (nb: provisional research only \u2013 see Talk page)\n* [http://www.shapcumbria.co.uk Shap Community Website \u2013 Maintained by the Parish Council]\n* [http://www.gravestonepix.com/contents1a/2009/10/shap-air-crash-anniversary/ Shap Air Crash Anniversary]\n* [http://www.gravestonepix.com/contents1a/2009/10/rail-workers-monument-shap/ Rail Worker's Monument, Shap]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vfc4bBY8puE Video footage and history of Keld Chapel]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CK498sf-ujU Video footage of the Shap Wells Spa and Hotel]\n{{NSEW|[[Penrith, Cumbria|Penrith]]|[[Kendal]]|[[Maulds Meaburn]]|[[Haweswater Reservoir|Haweswater]]|||||}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Westmorland]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cumbria]]\n[[Category:Eden District]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toParish council(link changed toParish councils in England) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shap"}
{"title_page": "Mork & Mindy/Laverne & Shirley/Fonz Hour", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name = Mork & Mindy / Laverne & Shirley / Fonz Hour\n| genre = [[Cartoon series]]\n| director = [[George Gordon (animator)|George Gordon]]<br>Bob Hathcock<br>John Kimball<br>[[Rudy Larriva]]<br> [[Carl Urbano]]<br> [[Rudy Zamora]]\n| starring =[[Robin Williams]]<br>[[Pam Dawber]]<br>[[Conrad Janis]]<br>[[Henry Winkler]]\n| voices = [[Ralph James]]<br>[[Stan Jones (actor)|Stan Jones]]<br>[[Ron Palillo]]<br>[[Lynne Marie Stewart]]<br>[[Frank Welker]]<br>[[Shavar Ross]]<br>Mark L. Taylor \n| composer = [[Hoyt Curtin]]\n| country = USA\n| language = English\n| num_seasons = 1\n| num_episodes = 27\n| executive_producer = [[William Hanna]]<br>[[Joseph Barbera]]<br>Joe Ruby<br>Ken Spears\n| producer = Joe Ruby<br> Art Scott<br> Ken Spears\n| runtime = 1 hour\n| company = [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]]<br> [[Ruby-Spears|Ruby-Spears Enterprises]]<br> [[Paramount Television (original)|Paramount Television]]\n| distributor = \n| channel = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]\n| first_aired = {{Start date|1982|9|25}}\n| last_aired = {{End date|1983|9|3}}\n| preceded_by = ''[[The Fonz and the Happy Days Gang]]''<br>''[[Laverne & Shirley (1981 TV series)|Laverne & Shirley in the Army]]''\n| related = ''[[Mork & Mindy]]''<br> ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]''<br> ''[[Happy Days]]''\n}}\n'''''Mork & Mindy/Laverne & Shirley/Fonz Hour''''' is a 1982-1983 American [[Saturday-morning cartoon|animated television series]] produced by [[Hanna-Barbera|Hanna-Barbera Productions]] and [[Ruby-Spears|Ruby-Spears Enterprises]] in association with [[Paramount Television (original)|Paramount Television]], featuring animated versions of characters from the live-action sitcoms ''[[Mork & Mindy]]'', ''[[Laverne & Shirley]]'' and ''[[Happy Days]]'', all part of the same franchise. This [[Saturday morning cartoon|Saturday morning]] series lasted for one season on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]].<ref name=Daytime>{{cite book |last1=Hyatt |first1=Wesley |title=The Encyclopedia of Daytime Television |date=1997 |publisher=Watson-Guptill Publications |isbn=978-0823083152 |url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopediaofda00hyat/page/256/mode/2up|accessdate=19 March 2020|page=257}}</ref>\n\nThis show was divided into two segments: ''Mork & Mindy'' and ''Laverne & Shirley with Special Guest Star The Fonz''. The ''Laverne & Shirley'' half-hour was the second season of ''[[Laverne & Shirley (1981 TV series)|Laverne & Shirley in the Army]]'', with the addition of [[the Fonz]] and his dog Mr. Cool from the earlier cartoon ''[[The Fonz and the Happy Days Gang]]''.<ref name=Perlmutter>{{cite book |last1=Perlmutter |first1=David |title=The Encyclopedia of American Animated Television Shows |date=2018 |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |isbn=978-1538103739 |page=352}}</ref>\n\n==''Mork & Mindy''==\nIn the ''Mork & Mindy'' segment, in which [[Robin Williams]] and [[Pam Dawber]] voiced the title characters, a teenaged Mork is sent to Earth from planet Ork to observe the lives of human teenagers and enroll in a local school. As on the original show, Mindy McConnell and her father Fred (voiced by [[Conrad Janis]]) are the only Earthlings who know that he is an alien and he sends telepathic reports of his experiences to Orkan ruler Orson (voiced by an uncredited [[Ralph James]]). Unlike the original show, Mork is accompanied by his Orkan pet, a pink, six-legged, [[dog]]-like creature named Doing (voiced by [[Frank Welker]]) which is pronounced as \"Doyng\". Other characters in the show included Eugene (voiced by [[Shavar Ross]]), Hamilton (voiced by Mark L. Taylor), and Principal Caruthers (voiced by an uncredited [[Stan Jones (actor)|Stanley Jones]]).\n\n===Episode list===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"background:#ffffff\"\n|- style=\"color:#ffffff\"\n! style=\"background:#B11030; width:30px\"| N\u00ba\n! style=\"background:#B11030\"| Title\n! style=\"background:#B11030; width